<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Envoy Optimistic on Solving Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, February 5 (Xinhua) -- French president's special
envoy Bertrand Dufourcq said here Thursday that he was optimistic
about the prospect of solving the U.N.-Iraqi crisis over weapons
inspection through diplomatic means.
</P>
<P>
Dufourcq, secretary-general of the French Foreign Ministry,
made the remark before he left here for Cairo, Egypt, Thursday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that diplomatic efforts had resulted in
progress, and that these efforts should continue to solve the
crisis peacefully.
</P>
<P>
According to diplomatic sources, Iraq has agreed to open nine
of its presidential sites to U.N. arms inspectors. But the news
has not been confirmed by the Iraqi government.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic efforts are intensifying in Baghdad to avert a
possible American military action against Iraq. Among the
mediators are Russian president's special envoy Victor Posuvalyuk,
Secretary-General of the Arab League Esmat Abdel-Meguid, Turkish
Foreign Minister Ismail Cem and Palestinian envoy Azzam al-Ahmed.
</P>
<P>
The French special envoy, who arrived here Tuesday evening,
met with Iraqi President Saddam Hussein Wednesday and handed over
to Saddam a letter from French President Jacques Chirac which
contains proposals for defusing the current crisis through
peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Dufourcq also exchanged views with Meguid on the
current crisis between Iran and the U.N., which was triggered off
by Iraqi refusal to allow U.N. arms inspectors access to its
presidential palaces on ground of sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
The palaces are suspected of hiding banned weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
