<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-05 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Lodges Protest Over Turkish Threats on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, February 5 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus has lodged a protest to
the U.N. over recent Turkish threats to a military air base in
southern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The protest was made in a letter addressed Wednesday to
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan by Cyprus' Permanent
Representative to the U.N. Sotos Zackheos, Cyprus News Agency
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The military air base, situated near the western coastal town
of Paphos, was constructed within the framework of a joint
defense pact with Greece in 1993. It will be used by Greek air
force planes.
</P>
<P>
The base has been completed and was handed over to the
National Guard by the contractors last month, but its formal
inauguration will take place after the presidential elections this
month.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government has stated that the base was a
defensive project and would be used only when Cyprus suffers an
attack.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has said it would also protest the delivery of the air
base to the U.N. Secretary-General and the Security Council, and
threatened to take necessary counter measures. Turkish Cypriot
leader Ruaf Denktash has warned he would "break the wings" of
Greek aircraft that may be stationed at the base.
</P>
<P>
The letter of the Cypriot government to the U.N. said "as a
sovereign and independent state, the Republic of Cyprus does
nothing more but to exercise its inalienable right recognized by
the U.N. Charter and general international law, through the
enhancement of the defensive capabilities of National Guard."
</P>
<P>
After 24 years of occupation of northern Cyprus by Turkish
troops, Zackheos noted, the need for Cyprus "to take sufficient
measures to defend itself in the face of this continuing threat
becomes even more imperative."
</P>
<P>
The letter pointed out that Turkey maintains in the occupied
northern island "a force of 36,000 heavily armed troops which are
constantly upgraded and modernized."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot diplomat urged the U.N. chief "to remind the
Turkish government of its obligations and responsibilities under
the Charter of the U.N.." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
