<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Able to Prevent Use of Force Against Iraq: Yeltsin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 5 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
said here Thursday that his country can prevent the United States
from taking military action against Iraq, Russian media reports
said.
</P>
<P>
"We must not allow a strike by force, an American strike. I
told (U.S. President Bill) Clinton about it: no, we shall not
allow that," Yeltsin told Russian and Italian journalists in the
Kremlin ahead of his Italian visit scheduled to start on February
11.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said his stance has gained support from the
international community including France and Italy.
</P>
<P>
The president did not elaborate on how Russia would respond to
the possible U.S. military action.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the use of force against Iraq could fuel a new
world war.
</P>
<P>
The United States has threatened to launch a military strike on
Iraq, which refused to grant U.N. weapons inspectors access to
some 60 sites on grounds of national sovereignty, to force it to
allow unrestricted access to all sites.
</P>
<P>
Washington even refused to pledge that it would not use force
during the winter Olympics held in Nagano, Japan from February 7
to 22.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin noted that the tension caused by the crisis over Iraq's
weapons inspection has eased but he could not say for sure that
the situation has returned to normal.
</P>
<P>
A news bulletin issued by the Russian Foreign Ministry on
Thursday said that the threat of force against Iraq still exists
because the United States remains reluctant to settle the crisis
by political or diplomatic means. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
