<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-05 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Renews Military Control in Troubled Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, February 5 (Xinhua) -- The Lebanese government Thursday
renewed a military control for another six months in the country's
troubled eastern area of Baalbek-Hermel, the official National New
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The move came a week after the bloody clash between maverick
Shiite Muslim cleric Sheikh Sobih Tufeili and the government army,
in which eight people were killed, including four army personnel.
</P>
<P>
The clash was prompted by the refusal of Tufeili and his armed
followers to leave a seminary belonged to the Iranian-backed
Hezbollah which had to call in the government army for military
intervention.
</P>
<P>
Baalbek's military takeover was first imposed last November
when Tufeili launched an anti-government self-proclaimed "Hunger
Revolution," in an attempt to set up a mini state by prohibiting
government ministers and parliament members to enter the area.
</P>
<P>
After Thursday's regular cabinet session, Minister of
Information Bassem Al-Sabaa told reporters that the government had
decided to give the 3,000-strong troop another six-month mandate
to control the area in order to keep law and order.
</P>
<P>
He added the government decided to transfer the case of Tufeili
to the country's judicial council.
</P>
<P>
Tufeili has been at large since the clash and reportedly
hiding in the hills near his hometown of Brital in the area. The
government troops have surrounded the region in a hunt-down
operation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
