<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Gives Strong Support to Clinton on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 5 (Xinhua) -- In a round of interviews
with U.S. televisions, British Prime Minister Tony Blair Thursday
showed his support to U.S. President Bill Clinton on the issue of
the Iraqi crisis over U.N. weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
Blair told CNN that experience had told the world diplomacy
must be backed by military action before you can force Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein to comply with U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"We've got to recognize in the light of our experience with
Saddam Hussein that diplomacy simply won't work unless it's backed
up by the threat of force or indeed the use of force," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said it should not be seen as "machismo" but a way to force
Saddam to live up to its promises.
</P>
<P>
"It's important, not out of machismo or a test of international
virility, but in the interest of long-term world peace that Saddam
Hussein is made to back down," he added.
</P>
<P>
On the ABC's "Good Morning American" program, Blair said U.N.
weapons inspectors found "a vast arsenal" of chemical and
biological weapons, which he said was a violation of U.N. weapons
inspections resolutions.
</P>
<P>
He said he believed the use of force was one way to compel
Saddam to end the manufacture of those banned weapons.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that we can, by military capability, force him to
do the things that he should be doing, properly in abidance with
the Security Council resolutions that have already been passed,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
But Blair told the NBC's "Today" program that decision had yet
to be made when to take military action against Iraq and any
newspaper reports about a specific date for the attack would only
be speculations. He was referring to a British newspaper report
which said Feb. 17 had been chosen for a military attack.
</P>
<P>
"There are no decisions on these things that can or should be
taken as a matter of public debate; newspaper reports like that
are highly speculative," he said.
</P>
<P>
Blair arrived in Washington Wednesday night for a three-day
visit. He will hold talks with President Clinton, discussing a
wide range of issues including North Ireland, Iraq, the Middle
East, NATO expansion, European affairs and the Asian economic
turmoil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
