<HEADLINE> S. Africa Tries to Confirm Plane Detention in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 5 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has been
trying to confirm that Angola is holding two South Africans
reportedly on board a Ukrainian aircraft impounded this week,
foreign affairs spokesman Marco Boni said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
International news media earlier reported that Angola seized
an Antonov 26 and its crew, along with two South African
passengers after allowing it to land in Luanda Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The plane was reportedly chartered by a South African company,
SG Corporation. It allegedly made flights to the region
controlled by rebel forces -- the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
Angolan civil aviation officials were quoted as saying the
Antonov was on a list of aircraft which violated Angolan
airspace.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian plane is the second to be detained in Angola in
the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
A DC-4 plane carrying mining equipment and other freight from
South Africa to Andulo, central headquarters of the UNITA, was
forced down by an Angolan Mig fighter on January 22. Eight South
Africans on board were being held in a military camp.
</P>
<P>
Angolan security officials said the privately owned plane
contravened a travel and air ban the United Nations imposed on
UNITA last year for violating a 1994 peace accord ending the
civil war in Angola. 
</P>
</TEXT>
