<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Spent 1.6 Billion to Prop Sagging Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 5 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Canada spent 1.6
billion U.S. dollar reserves to shore up the sagging loonie in
January as it sank to its lowest levels in 140 years.
</P>
<P>
During January, the Canadian dollar lost 1.7 percent of its
value, breaking through the previous lows of 69.24 cents US
reached on February 4, 1986, and falling to 68.70 cents US at the
end of the month.
</P>
<P>
At Wednesday's close, the dollar was 69.11 cents US, up 0.03
cents US from the previous day, reports said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The dollar has regained some of its losses in the past few days
after the central bank raised interest rates half a percentage
point last week.
</P>
<P>
Market players will be scrutinizing a speech to be delivered
Thursday by Bank of Canada Governor Gordon Thiessen for future
trends in interest rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
