<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Families Eat Out Less </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 5 (Xinhua) -- Canadian families have been
eating out less, and spending more of their food dollars in the
grocery store, according to a Statistics Canada report.
</P>
<P>
The statistics show that between 1992 and 1996, Canadian
family spending on restaurant meals fell 6.5 percent. Over the
same span, spending on groceries rose by 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The figures are another sign of how Canadian families suffered
in the recession of the early 1990s and the idling economy of the
mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
"It's families tightening their belts," Gordon Betcherman, an
economist of Canadian Policy Research Networks, was quoted as
saying by reports Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Canadian families spent an average of 112.09 dollars
(77.4 US dollars) on groceries or in restaurants, up only 1.5
percent from that in 1992.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, restaurant meals prices were up 6.3 percent
and grocery store food prices up 5.8 percent, according to the
statistics agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
