<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Drug Sales Growth Slows Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 5 (Xinhua) -- The growth rate in sales of
drugs in 10 of the biggest pharmaceuticals markets in the world
slowed down in the year to November, according to the latest data
from specialist market researchers at IMS International.
</P>
<P>
The sales growth rate over the 12 months was 5 percent at 165.9
billion US dollars, compared with a 7 percent growth rate in the
year to October.
</P>
<P>
The main reason for the slowdown is that in the world's biggest
market, the US, growth in the period fell from 14 percent to 10
percent at 66.05 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, sales in the world's second largest market, Japan,
were down 1 percent at 42.4 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, sales in smaller markets rose. Drug sales in Italy and
Canada were up 5 and 11 percent at 8.6 billion dollars and 4.1
billion dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that by the medical area, heart drugs remained
the biggest sellers with sales up 5 percent at 33.7 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Nervous system drugs remained the fastest growing sector, with
sales 12 percent higher at 23.4 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
