<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Leader Visits Angola for Reconstruction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, February 5 (Xinhua) -- Joao de Deus Pinheiro, an
official in charge of the European Union's African, Caribbean and
Pacific affairs arrived at Luanda Thursday to try to strike deals
on EU's aid programs on Angola's reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
Pinheiro, who is on his three-day visit, said on arriving at
the Luanda airport here that he has come at a time when the
Lusaka Peace Protocol is to be fully implemented in Angola and an
enduring peace is to befall the country.
</P>
<P>
The EU is to increase its aid to Angola by 90 percent in the
coming five years as compared with the past five years, he said,
adding that he is to sign a 100 million U.S. Dollars aid plan
during his visit this time.
</P>
<P>
He said that the framework of EU's relations with the African,
Caribbean and Pacific region, which is now waiting for European
Commission's approval, is to bring a brand-new concept of
treating countries in these regions as sovereign states rather
than the formerly donors and recipients.
</P>
<P>
The EU would like to help the African, Caribbean and Pacific
region countries in its economic integration with the world on
the basis of political talks between sovereign countries, the EU
official said.
</P>
<P>
To reach these goals, he said, the EU should make great
efforts in strengthening the production and trade systems, and
offer technical and financial help to countries in the region if
necessary, so as to link them closely with the EU.
</P>
<P>
He said he would like to have an extensive contact with
Angolan leaders, so as to better understand the political
situation in the country and the strategic choice of the leaders
of the former rebel movement the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
The EU would naturally react to the new situation taking place
in Angola and to the strategic choice leaders in Angola are
taking, Pinheiro said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
