<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Factory Orders Register 2.5 Pct Drop in December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 5 (Xinhua) -- The orders from the U.S.
factories and plants registered a drop in December mainly by a
record plunge in orders for aircraft, but retailers prospered, the
Commerce Department reported here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 63 percent aircraft drop was the worst since the department
began tracking the industry in 1958, the report said. The decline
caused an overall 2.5 percent dip in factory orders, to a
seasonally adjusted 336 billion U.S. dollars. It was the worst
monthly drop in more than five years.
</P>
<P>
Excluding the volatile aircraft sector, orders rose a moderate
1.6 percent, with strength reported in demand for autos,
electrical equipment, industrial machinery, paper, chemicals and
food products.
</P>
<P>
Some economists believed the aircraft orders drop was one of
the first concrete signs that Asia's problems are hurting the U.S.
economy. Last week, Boeing Co. said it expected Asian customers
over the next three years to buy 60 fewer planes than anticipated
before the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Despite December's blow to aircraft manufacturers, factories
during all of 1997 reported a robust 5.3 percent orders increase,
compared with 4.6 percent in 1996 and 7.4 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Shipments of factory goods, which is regarded as a measure of
current production, rose 1.3 percent in December and were up 5.7
percent for the year as a whole. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
