<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Civil Unrest to Affect Zimbabwe's Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 5 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's riotous civil
protests against economic difficulties have the potential to
damage the country's fledgling tourism sector, which registers
the fastest growth in the last few years.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe National News Agency Ziana reported Thursday
that, coupled with the downward slide in the value of the
Zimbabwean Dollar against major international currencies, the
country is currently going through one of the worst economic
crisis since independence in 1980.
</P>
<P>
The unpredictable economic situation will likely cause more
civil unrest, Ziana report said.
</P>
<P>
The industry's performance in the past 10 years has been
commendable, generating 1.3 billion Zimbabwean Dollars (80
million U.S. Dollars) in 1995 and 2.3 billion (140 million U.S.
Dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 the sector earned 3.4 billion Zimbabwean Dollars (200
million U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Chairman of Zimbabwean Council for Tourism (ZCT), Herbert
Nkala said the industry's ambitious projected revenue in 1998 may
not be realized due to likely more civil unrest.
</P>
<P>
Nkala warned that the growth phase of the sector, which is the
third largest foreign currency spinner, was on the decline.
</P>
<P>
He said, unlike other sectors like agriculture where effects
of drought take long to be felt or mining where minerals can be
stockpiled until the price is right, tourism is highly vulnerable
to unpredictable harsh socio-economic conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
