<HEADLINE> S. Africa Proposes African Telcoms Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 5 (Xinhua) -- South Africa Thursday
appealed to set up a dedicated fund to support public and private
telecommunication infrastructure investment in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a workshop attended by African communications
ministers in Somerset, six km east of Cape Town, South African
Communications Minister Jay Naidoo said it was important, in
developing an African telecommunication strategy, to see how
private financing could be better used.
</P>
<P>
The workshop was held in preparation for the African Telecom
'98 Exhibition and conference to be held in Johannesburg in May.
</P>
<P>
Naidoo said an African plan of action for telecommunications
development should seek to initiate dialogue toward designing and
creating legal and regulatory frameworks.
</P>
<P>
It should also promote gradual introduction of competition in
providing advanced services, and improve the efficiency of public
telecommunication operations to prepare them for this
competition, he said.
</P>
<P>
A unified African position on telecommunications would ensure
that the continent achieved its vision of being an integral part
of the global information society, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the meeting, Henry Chasia, deputy
secretary-general of the International Telecommunication Union,
said Africa was the largest and last great untapped market for
telecommunication infrastructure, products and services.
</P>
<P>
It was the place on earth that offered the greatest returns to
those entrepreneurs willing to take the risk and a longer-term
point of view, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
