<HEADLINE> British Expert Calls for Education Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 5 (Xinhua) -- British educationist Barnaby
Shaw today said education reforms are a necessity as countries'
economies and societies continued to change.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a seminar at the on-going U.K.-Zimbabwe Cooperation
Week in Harare, Shaw, from UK's Department for Education and
Employment, said reforms were needed to raise performance in
schools.
</P>
<P>
"There has been a rise in demand for higher education, fast
change in the labor market and need for more technical skills,
and all these changes prompt the need for education reforms,"
Shaw said.
</P>
<P>
He urged governments to have national education commissions
which would look into the education system to give the best
possible recommendations for the benefit of it.
</P>
<P>
For education institutions, he said, they had to be clear on
what business needed, otherwise companies and organizations would
not be provided with the personnel they required.
</P>
<P>
"With the ever changing economic and social scenario," he
said, "gone are the times when there was demand for people who
are only academically sound, but with no practical experience."
</P>
<P>
He called for the need to respond to new demands for the
education system, and he commented the Zimbabwean government for
putting in place a commission on inquiry into education and
training.
</P>
<P>
The commission would look into various issues pertaining to
provision of education and training, organizational capacity and
management and financing the education system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
