<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soft Commodity Prices Fall 7 Pct in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 5 (Xinhua) -- The prices of soft commodity
fell by 7 percent last year and is forecast not to rise before
1999, according to the Economist Intelligence Unit (EIU).
</P>
<P>
The EIU said in its latest analysis of the soft commodity
market that although the prices of beverages, such as coffee,
cocoa and tea, rose 29.9 percent last year, a 24.5 percent fall in
the price of grain helped drive the soft commodity price basket
down sharply by 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The report predicted that this year, cane sugar supplies would
fall due to the effects of El Nino, which in turn would force up
raw sugar prices by 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, a probable 12.1 percent decline in the prices of
beverages due to plentiful supplies of coffee, cocoa and tea would
offset sugar's gains and bring about a 1.1 percent fall in the
overall soft commodity price basket.
</P>
<P>
The EIU downgraded its forecast for global maize consumption as
a result of the fall-out from the east Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
It predicted that commodity prices would rise by an average 3.7
percent in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
