<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Vows Retaliation If Attacked by Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 5 (Xinhua) -- Israel on Thursday insisted
on its right of self-defense against a possible Iraqi missile
attack despite U.S. advice that it refrain from retaliation.
</P>
<P>
In response to U.S. Secretary of Defense William Cohen's call
for Israeli low profile, the Prime Minister's Office issued a
statement reiterating Israel will make its own decision.
</P>
<P>
"As we have always said, Israel reserves the right to
self-defense and will act based on its security interests," the
statement said. "This position has not changed."
</P>
<P>
As the U.S.-Iraq standoff over weapons inspection continued
escalating, there were widespread fears here that Iraq might
launch biological or chemical attack on Israel if the U.S. takes
military actions against Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Worried citizens flooded gas masks distribution centers around
the country. For most Israelis, the memory is still vivid about
the Scud missile attack launched by Iraq during the 1991 Gulf
War. At that time, Israel was forced to refrain from retaliating
under U.S. pressure.
</P>
<P>
To prevent a public panic over the Iraqi crisis, Israeli
leaders in recent days repeatedly assured its citizens that the
chance of an Iraqi attack is very low this time. They also vowed
that if attacked, Israel would retaliate with close coordination
with the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Ariel Sharon, national infrastructure minister and member of
the inner security Cabinet, said Thursday that Israel should not
be pressured on the matter of self-defense. He said that facing a
web of conventional and non-conventional threats, Israel must
carry out essential measures to defend its own citizens.
</P>
<P>
Opposition Labor Party leader Ehud Barak also came out to
support the government position. After meeting with U.S.
Ambassador to Israel Edward Walker, Barak said Cohen's appeal to
Israel to stay idle toward Iraqi attack was "unhelpful."
</P>
<P>
He added that Israel has the right to reply to any attacker,
although he believed that such retaliation must be carried out in
a careful way and with close coordination with Washington.
</P>
<P>
In the past week, Israeli leaders held a flurry of high-level
consultations on the Iraqi crisis and possible answers to possible
Iraqi attack.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu held
discussions on the Gulf situation with Sharon, Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai, Industry and Trade Minister Natan Sharansky as
well as Barak.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Netanyahu is scheduled to brief international
diplomats based in Israel on the Gulf situation and Israel's
position. 
</P>
</TEXT>
