<HEADLINE> Krupp Approves Overall Merger With Thyssen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 5 (Xinhua) -- Germany's industrial concern Krupp
Thursday approved plans to merge with its rival Thyssen into a
giant industrial and technological group, said reports reaching
here from Essen.
</P>
<P>
Thyssen approved the overall merger plans on January 22.
</P>
<P>
The two giants had merged their steel units in September 1997.
Negotiations on overall merger started later.
</P>
<P>
Krupp's supervisory board ordered the management board to clear
up the remaining details and negotiate a final deal with Thyssen.
</P>
<P>
Coal and steel are expected to amount to less than half of the
business of the new company, which will have some 180,000
employees and a 60 billion mark (33.4 billion US dollar) turnover.
</P>
<P>
In the 1996-97 business year ending last September 30, Thyssen
posted a record pre-tax profit of 3.3 billion marks (1.8 billion
dollars) on turnover of 40.8 billion marks (22.7 billion dollars).
</P>
