<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Authorizes to Extend MISAB Mandate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 5 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council of
the United Nations today authorized extension of the mandate of
the Inter-African Mission to Monitor the Implementation of the
Bangui Agreements (MISAB) until March 16, 1998.
</P>
<P>
In its resolution, the Security Council welcomed the efforts
made by the member states participating in the MISAB and by those
states providing support to the team, and their readiness to
maintain these efforts.
</P>
<P>
It welcomed the support provided by the United Nations
Development Program to the International Committee for the
follow-up of the Bangui Agreements and encourages it to continue
this support.
</P>
<P>
It called upon the parties in the Central African Republic to
complete the implementation without any delay of the provisions of
the Bangui Agreements.
</P>
<P>
The council welcomed the intention of the secretary-general to
appoint a special representative to the Central African Republic
and expressed its belief that the prompt appointment of such a
representative could assist the parties in the implementation of
the Bangui Agreements and provide support to other activities of
the United Nations in the country.
</P>
<P>
The council reiterated its call to all states, international
organizations and financial institutions to assist in
post-conflict development in the Central African Republic.
</P>
<P>
The council requested the secretary-general to submit a report
for its consideration, no later than February 23, 1998, on the
situation in the Central African Republic with recommendations
regarding the establishment of a United Nations peacekeeping
operation, including the structure, specific goals and financial
implications of such an operation.
</P>
<P>
The council expressed its intention to take a decision by March
16, 1998 on the establishment of a United Nations peacekeeping
operation in the country.
</P>
<P>
The MISAB, established in February 1997 at the invitation of
the president of the Central African Republic and with the
authorization of the Security Council of the United Nations, aims
to help the country restore peace and stability. France provides
logistical and financial support for the team.
</P>
<P>
But the French government has announced withdrawal of its
support for the mission beginning in mid-April. UN
Secretary-General Kofi Annan has recommended establishment of a UN
peacekeeping force to succeed the MISAB when its mandate ends in
March 16, 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
