<HEADLINE> Saddam: Iraq Ready to Face Any Challenge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, February 5 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
said Thursday that while Iraq is willing to continue diplomatic
efforts to defuse current crisis, its people are ready to face
any challenge.
</P>
<P>
Saddam made the remark when meeting with Palestinian special
envoy Azam al-Ahmed, who delivered a letter from Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat, the Iraqi news agency INA reported.
</P>
<P>
INA said that in his message, Arafat said Palestine rejects
firmly the American threat of using force against Iraq and stands
by the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
In the evening, Saddam chaired a joint meeting of the
Revolution Command Council and the ruling Baath Party to briefed
the attendants the contents of his meetings with Russian and
French presidents' special envoys.
</P>
<P>
However, INA did not elaborate on the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi president met with General-Secretary of the Arab
League (AL) Esmat Abdel-Meguid and Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail
Cem earlier today.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Abdel-Meguid, Saddam expressed his
appreiation of the position of Egypt and the efforts made by
President Hosni Mubarak to solve the current crisis through
diplomatic means.
</P>
<P>
Saddam stressed the important role that AL is playing and
expressed keenness to cooperate with Egypt and AL in settling the
crisis for the common interests of Arab nation.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid reiterated the opposition of all Arab nation to
the American military threat against Iraq and expressed hope that
the crisis would be solved through diplomacy in order to
maintain Iraq's sovereignty, dignity and national security.
</P>
<P>
Meguid said he would coordinate with all parties concerned
to contribute more to the settlement of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Saddam, the Turkish foreign minister
conveyed a verbal message from Turkish President Suleyman Demirel
that Turkey attaches importance to bilateral relations and hopes
the crisis can be defused through diplomatic and political means.
</P>
<P>
Cem expressed hope that measures could be taken to prevent
the tense situation from further deteriorating and said that
Turkey respects Iraq's sovereignty and territorial integrity.


