<HEADLINE> Iran to Continue Supporting Lebanese Resistance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, February 5 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Iranian Majlis
(parliament) Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri Thursday said that his
country has and will continue to support Lebanese resistance
against Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
Nouri made the remarks during his talks with Lebanese House
Speaker Nabih Berri. Their talks touched on various issues,
including bilateral ties, the stalled Middle East peace process,
recent Lebanese Muslim unrest, the U.N.-Iraqi arms inspection
crisis and Turkey-Israeli military alliance.
</P>
<P>
He accused Israel of pursuing hardline policy which led to
the deadlock of the peace process, saying Israel does not want
real peace but work hard to gain more time and eventually
get more Arab land.
</P>
<P>
He also said the Turkish-Israeli military alliance cannot be
ignored, stressing the need to coordinate to face the threat.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on recent Lebanese crackdown on an unrest led by
the former Iranian-backed Hezbullah leader sheikh Sobhi Tufeili in
the impoverished eastern area of Baalbek-Hermel, the Iranian
parliament leader said he deplored the violence which killed eight
people, adding the issue is a Lebanese internal affair.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hopes that Lebanese government will deal with
it in accordance with state laws.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Berry stressed the importance of Nouri's
visit, the first of its kind, to Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
He said the timing of the visit is very important in light of
the regional tension, stressing the need to close ranks to
confront Israel which has been attempting to weaken Lebanese
resistance.
</P>
<P>
Israel has been occupying a 1,200-square-kilometer area in
south Lebanon since 1985 with the aim to protect its north
from cross-border guerillas attacks. The occupation prompted a
13-year-old resistance from Lebanese guerrillas which is
spearheaded by Hezbullah.
</P>
<P>
Nouri arrived here Thursday morning from Damascus. During his
two-day visit, he will also meet with Lebanese President Elias
Hrawi, Prime Minister Rafik Hariri and tour south Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
