<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Warns Iraq of Grave Consequences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, February 5 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia warned Iraq
Thursday that it would face "grave consequences" if it continues
to bar the U.N. inspectors the access to suspected Presidential
Palaces, an official statement by the Saudi Foreign Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The statement issued following talks between visiting British
Foreign Secretary Robin Cook and his Saudi Counterpart Saud
Al-Faisal in Riyadh said "a failure to resolve this crisis through
diplomatic means will lead to grave consequences" and Iraqi leader
Saddam Hussein is to blame for the consequences.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia and Britain urged Iraq to comply fully with the
U.N. Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the two sides stressed the importance of
finding a diplomatic solution for the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in a joint news conference with Al-Faisal, Cook
said "we both agree that there will be grave consequences if
Saddam does not comply with U.N. Security Council resolutions,
and we both agreed that in that event it will be Saddam Hussein
alone who will be responsible for the consequences."
</P>
<P>
Cook arrived in Riyadh late Wednesday night on a regional
tour which would also cover Kuwait to discuss the recent
Iraq-UN standoff. 
</P>
