<HEADLINE> Yeltsin: Russia Disallows Military Solution to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 5 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
Thursday believed the peak of tension around Iraq is over and
stressed again that Russia would not allow a military solution of
the problem, according to the ITAR-TASS.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin told reporters Thursday on the eve of going to Italy
for a visit, "We should not allow an armed strike, an American
strike, whatever the circumstances."
</P>
<P>
But he added, "One cannot be sure so far that everything is all
right, that another heightening of tension is out of the
question."
</P>
<P>
The president warned again that military strikes might trigger
another world war. He said, "The most important thing is that we
assumed a really firm stand: no to a military solution of the
problem. It is impossible; it will mean a world war."
</P>
<P>
Russia's position is backed by France and Italy while Britain
is still hesitant, according to Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
During the telephone conversation Wednesday, British Prime
Minister Tony Blair promised to Yeltsin that he would no longer
send military hardware to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Russian president Wednesday warned U.S. President Bill
Clinton by telephone that using force to resolve the Iraqi crisis
might provoke a world war.
</P>
<P>
The United States stated on the same day that it had no plan
and did not intend to use nuclear weapons against Iraq. 
</P>
