<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Far Fewer People Join Nationwide Jobless Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 5 (Xinhua) -- Far fewer people than expected
took part in the long-planned nationwide protests in Germany
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Police estimates by mid-afternoon showed less than 20,000
people joined the protests, compared to over 1 million earlier
anticipated.
</P>
<P>
The protests were called by trade unions, churches and the
opposition Greens Party against Germany's mass unemployment,
which had been at high levels since the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
The protests coincided with the Thursday release of official
unemployment figures for January, which showed that unemployment
in Germany surged by 301,600 to a record high of 4.823 million, or
12.6 percent from December's 11.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Labor Office blamed the January increase on
seasonal factors. It reported that on a seasonally-adjusted basis,
unemployment dropped by 72,000 to 4.46 million.
</P>
<P>
According to the office, the gap in joblessness continued to
widen between western and eastern Germany, with the rate being
10.5 percent in the west and 21.1 percent in the east.
</P>
<P>
About 11,000 people joined the demonstrations in eastern
Germany.
</P>
<P>
Among the most popular banners carried by protesters were
"(Chancellor Helmut) Kohl has to go!" and "We need work!"
</P>
<P>
The nationwide jobless protests were projected following the
example of France. But police said that, compared to the protests
in France, the demonstrators were not only fewer, but also
peaceful.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, Karlsruhe and Oldenburg, protestors only briefly
blocked the entrances to state-run employment agencies.
</P>
<P>
Organizers said the low turnout was due to a "feeling of shame"
among the unemployed.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition Social Democrats (SPD) in a heated debate
at parliament held Kohl's center-right government responsible
for the situation in Germany, deeming the widening gap between the
rich and the poor in the country as a major cause.
</P>
<P>
Kohl's party said Germany needed to improve the investment
environment in order to create more jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
