<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Says Asia Rescue Must Shield Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 5 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF) today expressed concern about the efforts
to rescue East Asia's sagging economies, saying it was not clear
that children would be protected from the effects of severe fiscal
austerity.
</P>
<P>
"Unless there are explicit safeguards for social programs,
efforts to ease the region's financial problems will cause great
suffering for children," said Carol Bellamy, UNICEF' executive
director.
</P>
<P>
Bellamy noted that the World Bank and the International
Monetary Fund have stressed the importance of protecting the
social sector. But she said the austerity measures prescribed for
the East Asian economies might make it difficult, if not
impossible, to protect social programs.
</P>
<P>
"We know from bitter experience that the imposition of the
stringent austerity can trigger wrenching social disruption -- and
that in these situations, children are always most at risk," she
said.
</P>
<P>
The likelihood that millions will be thrown out of work makes
the prospects for children that much more dire, the executive
director said.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF's concern, Bellamy said, is that the region be spread
the steep declines in human development that the same kind of
measures wreaked on the developing world beginning nearly two
decades ago.
</P>
<P>
Bellamy said UNICEF does not question the need for economic
adjustment in developing countries facing serious financial and
trade problems. Nor, she said, does UNICEF believe that there are
any painless solutions to the East Asia crisis.
</P>
<P>
"We are all too familiar with the experience of the 1980s, when
dozens of countries in Africa and Latin America were obliged to
accept structure adjustment, but without a human face," Bellamy
said.
</P>
<P>
"The result was a `lost decade' of deepening poverty, rising
inequality, slow growth, and mass unemployment -- a slow-motion
social catastrophe whose effects are still being felt. That
history must not be allowed to repeat itself," she stressed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
