<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Farmers Urged to Fully Tap Wild Gum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, February 5 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian farmers were
Thursday urged to fully tap wild gum resource in a bid to
increase gum export to world market.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ethiopian News Agency, the head of Gum
Production Trade Department of the country, Tiruwork Woldehana,
said the foreign currency earned from the sale of gum is very low
owing to lack of awareness on the part of the farmers.
</P>
<P>
She said peasants are using wild gum for fuel wood and other
purposes, thus the hard currency obtained in the sector has been
minimal.
</P>
<P>
The head said that the wild gum found along the Ethio-Sudan
borderline have an international market and that most of the item
is being sold to European, Middle-east and Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
However, she said although efforts have been exerted to deploy
the inhabitants of northern Tigray Regional State who are
experienced in collecting gum to places where gum is found, it
has been impossible to fully tap the resource due to shortage of
manpower engaged in the sector.
</P>
<P>
Wild gum could serve as an ingredient for medicines and a raw
material in pulp and gum factories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
