<HEADLINE> Canada to Boost Film Industry: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 5 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government will
revamp its cultural policies to encourage more Canadian film
production and distribution, said Heritage Minister Sheila Copps.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously, the current policies are not working," the minister
was quoted as saying by Thursday's reports.
</P>
<P>
Canada is a huge market for films with a box-office total of
400 million dollars (280 million US dollars) in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the box office receipts for Canadian films have remained
unchanged at 2 percent of the total market since 1984.
</P>
<P>
It is essential to change the distribution and marketing of
Canadian films, whose number rose to 61 in 1995 from 55 in 1992,
Copps said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said she hopes that a new policy will be in place
by this time next year.
</P>
<P>
Some of the steps that the government wants to pursue will
include distribution legislation, tougher foreign investment
rules, new subsidies for the film industry and quotas that could
be imposed on theaters and video rental stores. 
