<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Firms Asked to Report Year 2000 Risks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 5 (Xinhua) -- Canada's public companies have
been asked to disclose Year 2000 computer risks to shareholders or
face sanctions ranging from a million-dollar fine to a cease-trade
order.
</P>
<P>
Securities regulators from across the country issued their 2000
requirements to public companies in a joint notice this week.
</P>
<P>
And they expect disclosures to appear in 1997 annual reports
this spring, according to Thursday's Financial Post newspaper.
</P>
<P>
"We and other financial regulators view the year 2000 problem
very seriously," said Jack Geller, acting chairman of the Ontario
Securities Commission.
</P>
<P>
"If the year 2000 risks could be putting you out of business,
or could be obligating you to make very substantial expenditures
to stay in business, then that may well be a material matter that
should be disclosed to your shareholders," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The year 2000 risks arise from the practice of computers using
only two digits rather than four to indicate the year portion of
the date.
</P>
<P>
When January 1, 2000, arrives, the computer will change from
"99" to "00" and react as if it's 1900 rather than 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
