and examined the Merkava III tank that Israel has sought to sell
to the Turkish armed forces.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Turkey last November, Mordechai tried to
persuade Turkey to purchase the Merkava, Israel's main battle tank.
</P>
<P>
Israel is bidding in competition with four other countries for
a lucrative deal to supply Ankara with thousands of tanks, which
would be assembled in Turkey. If Israel wins the bid, it will be
the first time that a Merkava is sold to a foreign country.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Turkish defense ties have been further strengthened by
Mordechai's November visit to Ankara, which also deeply enhanced
the strategic alliance between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
As the first Israeli defense minister visiting Turkey,
Mordechai said during his stay in Ankara that Israel was willing to
share with Turkey advanced weapons technology to combat the
threats facing the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Apart from helping Turkey to upgrade its F-4 and F-5 jet
fighters, Israel is also offering to upgrade Turkey's aging M-60
battle tanks and sell Turkey anti-tank missiles, the
air-to-ground Popeye missiles and the Galil assault rifles.
</P>
<P>
In January, naval vessels from Israel, Turkey and the United
States held a one-day joint exercises in the Mediterranean
Sea. 
</P>
