<HEADLINE> Haphazard Issuance of Driving Licences in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, February 5 (Xinhua) -- Haphazard issuance of
driving licences is one of the major reasons for the high rate of
traffic accident in Tanzania, the country's Travellers' Service
Association has said.
</P>
<P>
The general secretary of the association, Cyprian Mhina, told
reporters Thursday in Dar es Salaam that the driving skills of a
number motorists are questionable, but they have acquired driving
licences unscrupulously.
</P>
<P>
"Our research has revealed that about 90 percent of motorists
in Tanzania are holders of class "C" driving licence, which is
difficult to obtain.
</P>
<P>
The official said he is also alarmed by the fact that many
teenagers also hold such kind of driving licence.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to the government to look into the matter and take
stringent measures to check the abnormal phenomenon and revise
procedures to control the "unnecessary and avoidable accidents."
</P>
<P>
Tanzania has recorded high rate of traffic accidents. In the
worst accident this year, 25 people were killed when a bus
overturned in the Coast Region on January 14.
</P>
<P>
The dangerous situation must be redressed, he said, otherwise
the country will see more and more ghastly accidents.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Mahina lashed out at the corrupt officials
who took bribery during driving qualification tests, saying they
should also be held responsible for the traffic accidents.
</P>
<P>
Mhina said his association is registering the number of
drivers across the country, which will help relevant authorities
to manage motorists in the future.
</P>
<P>
The registration, which started last June, is progressing well
in urban areas but at a snail's pace in the countryside because
of El Nino rains.
</P>
<P>
So far, he said, they have been able to register about 100,000
drivers. But drivers in Dar es Salaam, with an estimated number
of 450,000, have yet to respond positively -- not more than 8,000
drivers have got registered with the association. 
</P>
</TEXT>
