<HEADLINE> Canadians Spend Less Time on TV, Radio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 5 (Xinhua) -- Canadians spent less time glued
to their televisions and radios in the fall of 1996, Statistics
Canada reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Compared with 1995, Canadians spent on average almost half an
hour less per week in front of the tube, and almost an hour less
listening to the radio.
</P>
<P>
Viewers watched television an averaged of 22.8 hours a week in
the fall of 1996, less than the 23.2 hours a week in 1995.
</P>
<P>
For radio, it was the third straight year of declining
audiences. Canadians tuned in an average of 20.2 hours a week in
1996, nearly an hour less than in 1995 and almost 90 minutes less
than the peak of 21.6 in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The figure also showed that Canadian women watched more
television than men, and both men and women aged 60 and over
watched more television than younger people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
