<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Opposes Use of Force Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, February 5 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon Thursday formally
announced that it opposes the use of military force against Iraq
over weapons inspection crisis.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made by the Minister of Information Bassem
Al-Sabaa after a regular cabinet session.
</P>
<P>
He said that during the session, President Elias Hrawi
suggested that the government should express Lebanon's opposition
to any military solution to the Iraqi issue.
</P>
<P>
Hrawi pointed out that Arab countries are intensifying
contacts and consultations, including the visit to Iraq by Arab
League Secretary General Esmat Abdel-Meguid, in a bid to avoid a
new disaster falling on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
But some diplomatic efforts are also being made in the Middle
East aimed at lobbying Arab countries' support to stage a military
strike on Iraq, he added.
</P>
<P>
Why must international resolutions about Iraq be complied with
and while others concerning Syria and Lebanon can be overlooked,
he asked, referring to Israel's refusal to implement the
U.N. resolutions to withdraw its occupying troops from Syria's
Golan Heights and South Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Even though Lebanon and Iraq have no diplomatic ties, Lebanon
will stand with most of the Arab countries opposing the use of
force against Iraq, the president said.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Lebanon and Iraq began to sour in 1990 due to
Lebanon's opposition to Iraqi invasion of Kuwait. The ties were
severed in 1994 when two Iraqi diplomats were involved in the
assassination of an Iraqi opposition leader in Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
