<HEADLINE> Britain Warns of Attack on Iraq If Diplomacy Fails </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, February 5 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary
Robin Cook Thursday warned that Iraq would face military strike if
it continued to turn a deaf ear to diplomatic initiatives seeking
to end the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
Cook made the remark at a press conference here at the end of
his shuttle visit to Kuwait aimed at coordinating its stand on the
current Iraqi crisis with its Gulf allies. His visit also took him
to Saudi Arabia earlier Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"That is why we exploring every possible diplomatic effort,
that is why we also apply every possible pressure on Saddam" to
comply with the U.N. resolutions, Cook said.
</P>
<P>
He said his country could not leave Iraqi leader Saddam
Hussein possessing chemical and biological weapons and further
delaying the work of the U.N. arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The inspectors have closed down Saddam's nuclear and long-range
missile programs and "what is now very important is to achieve the
same progress on the chemical and biological weapons," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot turn a blind eye to Saddam Hussein, for he
obstructs and delays the work of U.N. inspectors," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said Britain was taking part with the U.S. in making clear
that "the military option is still there and Saddam Hussein is
making a big mistake if he calculated that we would not use that
option."
</P>
<P>
He said Saddam Hussein "must take the responsibility of the
consequences of a military action" if he does not give a chance to
a diplomatic solution to resolve Iraq's standoff with the U.N.
Special Commission in charge of scrapping Iraqi mass destruction
weapons.
</P>
<P>
Cook, who was on his first visit to Kuwait since he took
office, visited Saudi Arabia and Kuwait amidst escalating pressure
on Saddam Hussein to respect the U.N. resolutions by allowing the
U.N. arms inspectors to enter all sites suspected of containing
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival in the Gulf state Thursday afternoon, Cook
held talks with Kuwaiti Emir Sheikh Jaber Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah on the
Iraqi crisis, the regional stability and the Kuwaiti security.
</P>
<P>
Cook said "Britain is interested in the peace and stability of
the Gulf region and wishes to work closely with governments in
the Gulf in resolving this crisis."
</P>
<P>
He will leave Kuwait for home Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released by Kuwaiti Information Ministry after
the conference, Kuwait said it supports the determined position
of the United Kingdom and its keenness on pressuring Iraq into
abiding by the U.N. resolutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
