<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Blair Stand Firm against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton and British Prime Minister Tony Blair on Thursday
showed their determinations to force Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein to back down from his stand on his refusal to allow
weapons inspectors's access to his presidential areas.
</P>
<P>
Both leaders will hold talks, mainly on the possibility of
military action against Iraq, once they decide that all the
diplomacy has been exhausted to resolve the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
"In the end, it is up to Saddam Hussein. It is not up to the
rest of us... I haven't talked to a single soul who hopes there
will be some sort of violent encounter here -- not a soul,"
Clinton said at an arrival ceremony for Blair's three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
Blair took a similarly hard line against Saddam at the
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
"We want a diplomatic solution to the crisis, but the
success or failure of diplomacy rests on Saddam. If he fails to
respond then he knows that the threat of force is there and it
is real," he said.
</P>
<P>
Before starting his talks with Blair, Clinton said any
military attack on Iraq would not take Saddam as a target, which
was in fact a response to Congress leaders who on Wednesday
urged to remove the Iraqi president by the use of force.
</P>
<P>
To remove Saddam from power "is not what the United Nations
has authorized us to do; that is not what our immediate interest
is about," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"Our interest is in preventing Saddam Hussein from building
biological, chemical, nuclear weapons capability and the
missiles to deliver such weapons," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
