<HEADLINE> Blair Asks U.S. to Help End IRA Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 5 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair today appealed to U.S. lawmakers to help stop violence by
the Irish Republican Army (IRA) if it fails to win its stated
demands at current peace talks in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Meeting some 20 senators and House representatives for
breakfast on the second-day visit to Washington, Blair said he
hoped to win over the powerful Irish-American lobby to his peace
strategy.
</P>
<P>
"We need your continuing help," said Blair in addressing the
lawmakers. If a settlement was achieved this would be "only the
beginning" and U.S. help would be vital in ensuring there were
real dividends from peace, he said.
</P>
<P>
The British prime minister, who had stated his nation's support
to the U.S. position for military action to force Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein to comply with U.N. resolutions, also expressed
gratitude for the support of U.S. President Bill Clinton in his
peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
Blair said: "We have succeeded in bringing Sinn Fein (political
wing of IRA) into the process, despite the obvious difficulties
this poses for us after long years of IRA terrorism, and clearly,
this was an important step."
</P>
<P>
He said, "I remain determined to keep the talks inclusive, and
to turn the men of violence once and for all onto the path of
democratic politics. This means that any return to violence cannot
and will not be countenanced."
</P>
<P>
"We must all make clear that violence can never be an answer in
Northern Ireland," Blair added.
</P>
<P>
The British prime minister said his remarks applied to
everybody in Northern Ireland, but the Reuters news agency said
"it was clear he was particularly eager to ensure that the IRA
would find no more sympathy in Washington if it ended its current
cease-fire."
</P>
<P>
"This is one area where your help is essential," Blair told the
U.S. lawmakers. "You have excellent contacts, which I hope you
will use. I hope too these contacts will continue to be with both
sides."
</P>
<P>
The IRA's current cease-fire, which began last summer, allowed
Sinn Fein to join the Belfast talks when they began in September.
</P>
<P>
Blair's talks with U.S. leaders will also cover a number of
other issues, including Iraqi crisis, Mideast peace process, Nato
expansion, military deployment in Bosnia, Asian financial crisis
as well as relations between the European Union and the United
States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
