<HEADLINE> White House Spokesman Criticizes Media Scandal Coverage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 5 (Xinhua) -- White House press secretary
said on Thursday that the rush by the news media to deliver
exclusive reports on the White House sex scandal has led to
erroneous stories.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry, referring to a Wall Street
Journal report which was posted on its Internet site on Wednesday
and later softened, said, "We went through one of the sorriest
episodes of journalism yesterday that I have ever witnessed."
</P>
<P>
"We had a daily newspaper reporting hour-by-hour, not giving
the White House any chance to assemble any facts and respond," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"If that's where we're marching off to, we're in a world of
hurt," McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper first reported that a White House steward told a
federal grand jury he saw Clinton and former intern Monica
Lewinsky alone together in a private study adjoining the Oval
Office.
</P>
<P>
After the lawyer for the steward, Bayani Nelvis, denied the
report the Journal revised the story on its Web site to say that
Nelvis described the incident to "Secret Service personnel" rather
than to a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
Paul Steiger, managing editor of the Journal, reportedly said
in a statement released by his New York office that his newspaper
went with its story "when we felt it was ready."
</P>
<P>
"We did not wait for a response from the White House because
the White House had made it clear repeatedly over the past two
weeks, in public and private, that they were not going to respond
to any questions or provide any information on any aspect of this
case," Steiger said.
</P>
<P>
"We stand by our account of what Mr. Nelvis told the Secret
Service," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has repeatedly denied allegations that he engaged in a
sexual relationship with Lewinsky and then asked her to lie about
it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
