<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia-Pacific Electricity Consumption Projected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 5 (Xinhua) -- The electricity consumption in
Asia-Pacific area is projected to be 11 percent lower in 2020 than
expected due to the recent economic turmoil and electricity
tariffs imposed by the countries concerned.
</P>
<P>
Entitled "Asia/Pacific Energy Outlook", a research paper said:
"As a result of both the currency crisis and economic slowdown,
many Southeast Asian countries have postponed power projects."
</P>
<P>
In Indonesia, for example, 13 private power projects have been
postponed. In Malaysia, the 2400 MW Bakun hydroelectric project
has been shelved because of the increasing ringgit cost.
</P>
<P>
In Thailand, as a result of the currency crisis, the PPAs of
the seven private power awards have been re-negotiated, according
to the paper by Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI.
</P>
<P>
DRI's forecast reflects the changing expectations concerning
capacity needs. Total installed capacity in Asia is forecast to
rise from 740 GW to 2002 GW by 2020 compared with 2265 GW forecast
last year.
</P>
<P>
Because of the Asian economic crisis, DRI expects capacity
additions to be 12 percent lower in 2020 than in last year's
forecast.
</P>
<P>
Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI, is the world's leading provider of
economic consulting and information services. It provides data,
analysis, forecasts and expert advice to more than 2000 business,
financial and government organizations worldwide.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
