<HEADLINE> Arab League Chief Ends Visit to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Secretary General of the Arab
League (AL) Ahmed Esmat Abdel-Meguid left Baghdad Friday, ending a
visit aimed at mediating a peaceful solution to the crisis of arms
inspection between Iraq and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the AL said Abdel-Meguid told Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein during their meetings that the Arab states have
unanimously rejected U.S. threats to use force against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The AL chief said that the Arab states are keen on seeking a
political settlement of the crisis, which will safeguard Iraq's
sovereignty, dignity and security.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has barred the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge
of eliminating Iraq's weapons of mass destruction from searching
presidential palaces suspected of hiding the banned weapons,
triggering its stand-off with the Untied States.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has threatened to take military actions to force Iraq
to grant free access to the UNSCOM if diplomacy fails to exact
Iraq's full compliance with U.N. arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid expressed his readiness to participate in the
efforts to find a political solution to the stand-off through
coordinating with concerned Arab and international parties.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, Abdel-Meguid also exchanged views with
France's presidential special envoy Bertrand Dufourcq on possible
solutions to the Iraq crisis.
</P>
<P>
They both agreed on the necessity to attain a compromise
settlement to end the crisis through diplomatic channels.
</P>
<P>
The visit of Abdel-Meguid, who arrived in Baghdad Wednesday, is
the first ever by an Arab League chief since the end of the 1991
Gulf War which drove Iraq out of Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
