<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU, Australia Sign Agreement to Boost Bilateral Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Australia and the European
Union have completed their negotiations on a mutual recognition
agreement on conformity assessment of products in a bid to boost
bilateral trade, said a statement issued by the EU on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Leon Brittan, vice-president of the European Commission, the
European Union (EU)'s executive body, and Australian Minister for
Industry, Science and Tourism, John Moore, made the announcement
in Brussels on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is aimed at facilitating trade by allowing
conformity assessment -- testing and certification -- of products
traded between the two sides to be taken in the exporting country
rather than to be carried out at destination.
</P>
<P>
"The agreement will provide a significant boost to two-way
trade. It will also open up markets to manufacturers for whom
regulatory costs have previously made exporting uneconomic," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
Brittan pointed out that this was an important step to enhance
bilateral trade relations.
</P>
<P>
It will deliver significant benefits to European industry,
affecting some 4.5 billion ECUs (some 4.8 billion U.S. dollars) of
bilateral trade, he added.
</P>
<P>
Moore said the fact that Australia has been able to conclude
such an agreement was a testimony to the high quality of the
Australian standards and conformance infrastructure and its
world-class reputation.
</P>
<P>
The agreement covers regulated sectors such as simple pressure
equipment, machinery, low-voltage electrical equipment and medical
devices, telecommunications terminal equipment and electromagnetic
compatibility. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
