<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coal Use Blamed for Shanghai Air Quality Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Air quality in Shanghai, the
busiest commercial city in east China, deteriorated in 1997 as a
result of increased coal consumption.
</P>
<P>
According to a report released recently by the city environment
monitoring center, the average concentration of suspended
particles and dust in the air dropped compared with 1996, but the
density of sulphur dioxide was up 15.3 percent and nitrogen oxide
by 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
Air quality experts said coal use was responsible for the
worsening air pollution. Last year Shanghai burned 40 million tons
of coal, or 60 percent more than 1990.
</P>
<P>
The report said water quality remained basically stable, but
that phosphorus pollutants were on the rise. The city gained some
improvement in noise control, with relevant indicators lower than
1996.
</P>
<P>
To improve air quality, Shanghai is readjusting its energy
structures by scaling down on coal use. Environmental officials
said the Donghai oil and gas fields will provide Shanghai with a
daily natural gas supply of 400,000 cubic meters by the end of
this year and the amount will increase to 1.2 million cubic meters
in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
