<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prominent Skilled Workers Awarded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 6 (Xinhua) -- A cook reputed as "the world's
best chef", a locomotive driver with no accident record in his
20-plus-year career, and eight other workers received here today
the country's top award for skilled workers--the China Grand Prize
for Professional Skills.
</P>
<P>
The ten award winners were also given a chance to meet Premier
Li Peng in Zhongnanhai, China's central government compound,
before vice premier Wu Bangguo bestowed each of them with a medal
made of 50 grams of pure gold. The medal was engraved with an
inscription from President Jiang Zemin: "National Model Skilled
Worker".
</P>
<P>
Apart from the ten, 101 other skilled workers selected from
China's over 100 million urban workers in various sectors were
also honored "National Model Skilled Workers" today.
</P>
<P>
Increasingly aware of the importance of technological
advancement and competent workers in economic development, the
Chinese government set up a national system in 1995 to discover
and honor the country's skilled workers doing an outstanding job.
</P>
<P>
The system requires the Ministry of Labor, along with 46
central government ministries and commission, and 31 provinces,
autonomous regions and municipalities, to search across the
country once a year for "National Model Skilled Workers", the top
ten of whom will become winners of the China Grand Prize for
Professional Skills.
</P>
<P>
Over the past three years, the ministry has honored 308
national model skilled workers and granted the grand prize to 30
most prominent workers.
</P>
<P>
The 30 prize winners come from 21 provinces, autonomous regions
and municipalities across the country, and are engaged in 25
different industrial sectors.
</P>
<P>
"They all deserve the grand prize for their skills which
represent the highest level in their own sectors," commented Wang
Xizhan, an official with the department of professional skills
under the labor ministry.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Renliang, a cook from Shanghai, was reported to be honored
in April 1996 "the world's best chef" by a service-appraisal
society in the US, and later engaged as senior tutor by a noted
culinary school in France.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Junqing, a locomotive driver from central China's Henan
Province, has reportedly been operating his train safely for 26
years, traveling over 1.4 million kilometers without any liability
accident.
</P>
<P>
An official with the labor ministry noted that though China has
a huge labor resource, the general quality of the country's
workers lags far behind that of the developed nations.
</P>
<P>
"In recent years in particular, with the retirement of the
older generation of skilled workers, China has been in a severe
shortage of competent workers," he added.
</P>
<P>
Workers with senior technical titles only account for 3.5
percent of China's skilled workers, while the general level in
developed countries is 20 to 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Before 2000, China will stick to the current system and try to
honor all prominent skilled workers in all sectors, to promote the
improvement of its labor quality," said Lin Yongsan, vice minister
of labor.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
