<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police Bugging Law Approved in Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Germany's upper house of
parliament, the Bundesrat, on Friday adopted a law allowing the
German police to bug criminal suspects in combating the rising
crimes.
</P>
<P>
The bill, worked out by the ruling party and the main
opposition Social Democrats (SPD) earlier last month, was passed
by the lower chamber, the Bundestag, on January 16.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, judges can approve the police to install
listening devices in the homes of the suspects of serious crimes
and the people who might commit serious crimes such as terrorism
against the public.
</P>
<P>
But the police will be barred from bugging the conversations of
criminal suspects with religious figures, their lawyers and
members of parliament. The use of the information bugged from
doctors and lawyers will also be limited.
</P>
<P>
As part of a deal for supporting the law, the government had
agreed with SPD to negotiate a complete ban on bugging journalists
and doctors.
</P>
<P>
The issue of police bugging had been debated in Germany for
years and such a need became more acute only in the 1990s as a
result of increased organized and violent crimes.
</P>
<P>
The latest available data show that violent crimes in Germany
increased 5.5 percent in 1996. The number of criminal cases
involving the use of firearms rose to 13,479 in 1996 from 12,855
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Manfred Kanther told the Bundesrat Friday
that 600 to 700 organized criminal groups with up to 8,000 members
are active in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
