<HEADLINE> Iraq's Neighbors Not to Allow Military Strike: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Secretary of Iran's
Constitutional Guardian Council Ayatollah Ali Jannati warned here
Friday that Iraq's neighbors would not allow any military strike
on Baghdad, the Iranian official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Friday prayers congregations, Jannati
criticized the behavior of the U.S. government toward Baghdad
and the U.S. handling of the issue of the U.N. arms inspections
in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"The people of the world are denied peaceful life because the
U.S. Administration is mischievous and too conceited," he said.
</P>
<P>
Jannati also urged the Iraqi government to do better to comply
with U.N. Security Council resolutions "so that the rogue
super-powers would not be able to exploit the situation."
</P>
<P>
Following the escalation of the tension between Iraq and the
U.S. over the U.N. arms inspection in Iraq, the Iranian
government expressed great concern over the situation, calling on
the international community and regional countries to use their
influences to avoid any possible military confrontation.
</P>
<P>
Tehran said that any military operations against Iraq would
only create new tension in the region and worsen the situation,
stressing that diplomatic efforts should continue to find a
political resolution to the stand-off between Iraq and the U.N.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud
Mohammadi strongly condemned the threatening statements by some
countries to use strategic nuclear weapons against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He said "such statements are against the whole region and none
of the regional countries will remain indifference to such
ill-considered statements." 
</P>
</TEXT>
