<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Okinawa Opposes Tokyo's Plan for U.S. Military Heliport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Okinawa Prefecture
Governor Masahide Ota on Friday rejected the central government's
proposal to build an offshore heliport for U.S. military forces.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in Haha, capital of Okinawa, Ota stressed
that the residents of Nago, the proposed site of the heliport,
voted overwhelmingly against the project in a non-binding
referendum held last December.
</P>
<P>
The governor even expressed his opposition to U.S. military
presence in Japan, adding that if the heliport plan was permitted,
it meant to allow the United States to establish its military
bases on Japan's territory.
</P>
<P>
The issue of U.S. stationing in Okinawa hit the central
government after anger erupted among the prefecture's residents in
1995 over the rape of a 12-year-old schoolgirl by three
U.S. servicemen.
</P>
<P>
Construction of a floating heliport was proposed, however, in
exchange for returning to Japanese jurisdiction the land that now
houses the U.S. Marine Corps Air Station Futenma in Ginowan.
</P>
<P>
With Ota's opposition to the heliport project made clear,
Japanese Prime Minister Ryuaro Hashimoto expressed his regret on
the same day that the return of the air base will be frozen.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Japanese Chief Cabinet Secretary Kanezo Muraoka
threatened to cancell a development scheme for the island
prefecture in retaliation for Ota's tough stance on this issue.
</P>
<P>
Two Okinawa-related panels of the ruling Liberal Democratic
Party (LDP) have decided not to carry out the planned revision of
the Okinawa promotion and development law, which is aimed at
creating a special free trade zone and easing taxes on businesses.
</P>
<P>
Okinawa accounts for less than one percent of Japan's total
land area, but contains about 75 percent of the land used by
U.S. military facilities in Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
