<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korean Labor Leaders Accept Layoffs for More Freedom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, February 6 (Xinhua) -- South Korean labor leaders agreed
Friday to legalize layoffs in return for more labor freedom after
three weeks of tough talks with employers.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement reached at a tripartite meeting of labor,
management and political figures, companies will be allowed to lay
off workers only when they face "emergency situations" such as
financial trouble, mergers or acquisition.
</P>
<P>
However, employers have to give a 60-day notice before they
dismiss workers, and they are also required to re-hire the
dismissed workers if their business improves.
</P>
<P>
Trade unions will be given the right to participate in
political activities in the first half of this year. Teachers will
be allowed to form unions from July 1999, while public officials
will be permitted to set up a "consultative body" as from early
next year.
</P>
<P>
The employment stabilization fund, which will be established
with the contributions from conglomerates, government and workers,
will be expanded by 5 trillion won (about 3.4 billion
U.S. dollars), 600 million won (about 2.7 million dollars) up from
the government's original proposal.
</P>
<P>
The agreement paves the way for the National Assembly
(parliament) to legalize a layoff bill, one of the key conditions
imposed by the International Monetary Fund in exchange for its 57
billion-dollar bailout package for South Korea, at its ongoing
special session.
</P>
<P>
Analysts predicted that some 1 million people will lose their
jobs when the layoff bill is passed this month.
</P>
<P>
Han Kwang-ok, a senior aide to President-elect Kim Dae-jung,
chaired the three-way panel on layoffs. He said the agreement will
help bring the nation out of the economic crisis triggered by the
failure of some conglomerates and bad loans of financial
institutions late 1997.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean cabinet endorsed the proposed bill and other
labor reform measures later in the day and submitted them to the
assembly for consideration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Christian Leader on Three-Self Patriotic Movement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Deng Fucun, vice chairman
and secretary-general of the Three-Self Patriotic Movement
Committee of the Protestant Churches of China, said Friday that
the aim of the movement is to make all Chinese Christians
patriotic citizens.
</P>
<P>
He said the three-self principles -- self-administration,
self-support and self-propagation -- have led to the increase of
the number of Chinese Christians from 700,000 in 1949 when the
People's Republic of China was founded to the current more than 10
million.
</P>
<P>
Deng made the remarks here at a seminar held at the Center for
Strategic International Studies.
</P>
<P>
Invited to talk about the Three-Self Patriotic Movement, Deng
said, it was unfortunate that Protestantism's introduction to
China last century coincided with the colonization process of the
nation by the Western powers; some missionaries played a
dishonorable role in it.
</P>
<P>
As a result, from the very beginning, Protestantism was deemed
an "alien religion" and not accepted by the Chinese public. During
the long period afterwards, a saying remained popular: "More
Christians, fewer Chinese" to mean that when a Chinese was
converted to Christianity, he would become an "alien" who bullied
his fellow Chinese.
</P>
<P>
In the 140-plus years prior to the founding of the People's
Republic of China in 1949, tens of thousands of missionaries were
sent to China by almost all Western nations at great
cost. However, only 700,000 Chinese became Christians because the
faith smacked of alienness and churches were run not by the
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
The founding of the People's Republic of China put an end to
the colonial rule by Western countries. Christianity in China
faced a practical choice: either remain an "alien religion"
rejected by the Chinese, or shed off its image by letting the
Chinese Christians organize independently churches acceptable to
the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Deng stressed that if a Chinese Christian wants to disseminate
the gospel, he should first be a good citizen of China. The
three-self principles are aimed at making Chinese Christians good
citizens. That is the main reason for the launch of the movement
by the church.
</P>
<P>
Deng said the the three-self patriotic movement has paid off in
the past 40 years, with Christianity no longer considered an
"alien religion" and the number of Chinese Christians increase by
more than 12 times. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujian Strengthens Health Supervision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Southeast China's Fujian
Province banned rampant treatment from 1,310 unauthorized medical
practitioners last year, local health officials said recently.
</P>
<P>
The province's health authorities also outlawed 1,021 illegal
hospitals or clinics, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
The health officials have overhauled 12,995 health
organizations and private drug stores, confiscating 13,116 kinds
of unqualified medicines valued at 538,000 yuan (about 65,000
U.S. dollars), they said.
</P>
<P>
Local enforcement groups have cracked down on 864 criminal
cases of fake medicine.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, Fujian standardized its regular check of food
vendors' stalls and cosmetics manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
The coastal province adopted health regulations in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
