<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Survivors Found at Philippine Crash Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Hopes for survivors are dimming
as rescuers on Friday picked up more mangled and decapitated
bodies at the crash site of a DC-9 plane on a southern Philippine
ridge.
</P>
<P>
Earlier television reports said about 46 dismembered bodies had
been retrieved by rescuers as of noon Friday at the crash site on
Mt. Sumagaya on the southern island of Mindanao. But so far, there
has been no official report on the number of recovered bodies.
</P>
<P>
Jesus Dureza, a leader of the rescue operation, told reporters
late in the afternoon that a total of seven cadavers of body parts
had been transported from the mountain to Cagayan de Oro City for
forensic examination.
</P>
<P>
He said it is very difficult to count the number of bodies and
identify them since most bodies are mangled.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said the airlift of the body bags from the crash
site to Cagayan de Oro has been hampered as helicopters can not
land at the area due to gusty winds, thick clouds and fog.
</P>
<P>
There is still no word from rescuers combing the crash site on
any survivors of the 104 people aboard the ill-fated Cebu Pacific
Flight 387, which crashed Monday into Mt. Sumagaya on its way to
Cagayan de Oro from Manila.
</P>
<P>
Rescue officials said earlier that it was a "remote
possibility" that any one could survive the air disaster, the
worst ever in Philippine history.
</P>
<P>
Government doctors who were sent to villages near the crash
site echoed the sentiment, saying that if there were any
survivors, they would have already died.
</P>
<P>
Rescue teams reached the impact point of the plane Friday
afternoon and found the wings, tail and two engines of the doomed
jetliner. But the "black box," the flight data recorder that will
pinpoint the cause of the accident, has not been recovered.
</P>
<P>
Rescue officials said it would take at least two months to
clear the crash site, an area of one square kilometer, and another
six months to undergo the painful procedure of identifying the
remains of crash victims.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
