<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Island Province Attracting Foreign, Domestic Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, February 6 (Xinhua) -- China's largest special economic
zone of Hainan is reporting good results in using foreign and
domestic investment to develop its local economy.
</P>
<P>
The island province has used 7.5 billion U.S. dollars of
overseas investment during the past decade since it was
established as a province, as well as 50 billion yuan of domestic
capital, accounting for 70 percent of its total investment in
fixed assets, involving more than 10,000 joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Hainan utilized 710 million U.S. dollars of overseas
investment in real terms, with foreign-backed businesses providing
100 million U.S. dollars worth of exports, up 30
percent. Meanwhile, domestic investment amounted to 3 billion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
The province approved 220 foreign-backed enterprises last year,
with 49 percent of them in primary industry and 42 percent in
secondary industry, considered a more rational proportion for the
province's industrial restructuring.
</P>
<P>
Some large groups began to show interest in the province, said
a government official, adding that Hainan plans to invite
investments of 1.2 billion U.S. dollars in 1998, 750 million of
which will be direct foreign investment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
