<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolia Enacts Law on Foreign Troop Deployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Mongolia on Friday published
its first law which will govern the stationing in and passing
through its territory of foreign troops.
</P>
<P>
Under the new law adopted by the Great Hural (parliament) on
January 8, Mongolia may invite foreign troops to station in its
territory if the country is under foreign armed aggression or is
in a de facto state of such aggression.
</P>
<P>
Foreign troops may also be deployed in Mongolia if the United
Nations Security Council has passed a resolution authorizing the
use of the U.N. peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
Mongolia will allow foreign troops to pass through its
territory or airspace if it believes that foreign governments'
request for such a permission does not infringe its security
interests.
</P>
<P>
However, Mongolia will not allow the troops of any of the
warring parties to station in or pass through its territory if the
warring parties have not constituted a threat to the national
independence and sovereignty of the country.
</P>
<P>
Although the troops of the former Soviet Union had been
stationed in Mongolia for a long time, there has been no law to
govern such deployment.
</P>
<P>
Mongolian officials explained that the adoption of the new law
does not mean that the country will soon invite foreign troops in
or allow itself to become a military base of foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
"It is just one of the basic laws of the country," they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
