<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Private Sector Debts Reach US$73 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's private sector had
borrowed a total of 73.962 billion U.S. dollars from abroad by the
end of December 1997, a official said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Radius Prawiro, head of the Steering Committee on Indonesia's
Private Sector Debts, said the country's total foreign debts have
reached 137.424 billion dollars, including 63.426 billion dollars
owed by the government.
</P>
<P>
The private sector's foreign debts are broken down into bank
loans (62.057 billion dollars) and commercial papers (11.905
billion dollars), Radius said after a meeting of the Economic and
Monetary Resilience Council led by President Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
"People should know that Indonesia's private sector debts have
broadly reached 73 billion U.S. dollars, which is not as big as we
previously thought," he said.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the size of mature private sector loans, Radius
said, "I can't say it, it is confidential."
</P>
<P>
Radius recently went to Japan to meet with Indonesia's Japanese
creditors.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, two groups were formed to handle the debt
problem -- a steering committee consisting of Japanese creditors
and a contact committee comprising Indonesian debtors.
</P>
<P>
"Japan has agreed to assign Bank of Tokyo Mitsubishi and Sanwa
Bank (to be included in the steering committee of creditors),"
Radius said, adding that the government has been approaching banks
in Europe about joining the steering committee of creditors.
</P>
<P>
Economists here hold that private sector debts were a main
cause of the depreciation of the Indonesian rupiah against the
U.S. dollar. The rupiah has dropped from 2,400 per dollar early
July last year to the present 10,000 a dollar.
</P>
<P>
Radius said his committee has also discussed the debt problem
with the World Bank affiliate, International Finance Corp., which
has provided loans to 42 companies in Indonesia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
