<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Visitor Arrivals in HK Expected to Rise in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hong Kong, February 6 (Xinhua) -- The total number of visitor
arrivals in Hong Kong in 1998 is expected to rise, in contrast to
the overall fall last year, a leading official of the Hong Kong
Tourist Association (HKTA) says.
</P>
<P>
Amy Chan, executive director of the HKTA, forecast an overall
increase of about two percent in the arrivals this year to reach
10.6 million, when commenting on the year-end results of the local
tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
The total number of visitor arrivals and tourism receipts for
1997 showed a drop of 11.1 percent and 14.7 percent respectively,
compared to the record year of 1996, according to HKTA figures.
</P>
<P>
Arrivals for the whole of 1997 were 10.4 million, which, while
down on the bumper year of 1996, were still higher than the 10.2
million for 1995.
</P>
<P>
The Americas were the only major market region to register an
increase in total arrivals, up by 7.3 percent to over one million.
</P>
<P>
The Northern Asian region, comprising Japan and South Korea,
showed the heaviest fall in 1997, with arrivals down by 37.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
The tourism receipts dropped in line with the arrivals. Total
receipts stood at 72.1 billion HK dollars (9.24 billion US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Other reasons for the decline include the currency depreciation
in Asia and a shortened length of stay by visitors (down three
percent to an average of 3.59 nights). There was also a moderate
drop in per capita spending of 4.6 percent to an average of 6,722
HK dollars (862 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
China's mainland was the largest contributor to visitors
spending receipts, accounting for 22.3 percent of the total,
followed by Taiwan, North Asia, South And Southeast Asia, Europe,
Africa and the Middle East, the Americas, Australia and New
Zealand and the South Pacific.
</P>
<P>
China's mainland registered an increase of 3.1 percent in per
capita spending.
</P>
<P>
The HKTA's new marketing campaign is designed to ensure Hong
Kong will be uppermost in travelers' minds so that it can be well
positioned for the business rebound, Chan said.
</P>
<P>
The HKTA expects that most markets, excepts for North Asia due
to the expectedly continued economic turmoil to depress outbound
travel, will begin to show an increase in arrivals by the end of
this year. It is looking to the Americas, China's mainland and
Taiwan to perform even better.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kim Dae-jung Firm in Restructuring Conglomerates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, February 6 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President-elect Kim
Dae-jung reaffirmed Friday his determination to restructure the
country's conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
"The new administration will not let the conglomerate
restructuring program fizzle out. The five-point accord reached
between me and business leaders last month should be implemented
without fail," Kim told the bosses of the nation's 30 largest
conglomerates at a luncheon.
</P>
<P>
Kim, who will be sworn in as president late this month, urged
the bosses to change their business practices to enhance
international competitiveness of South Korean businesses. He
promised that his government will give full legislative and
financial support to them.
</P>
<P>
Kim's renewed call for corporate restructuring came hours after
union leaders agreed to give employers the power to lay off
workers, ending a three-week long tough negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Kim said he will also protect the rights and interests of the
workers as much as he could.
</P>
<P>
The business leaders pledged to implement restructuring
measures they agreed early last month.
</P>
<P>
"We will change our business practices by holding general
meetings of shareholders soon and try to honor the agreement,''
said a statement issued by the business leaders after the luncheon.
</P>
<P>
Last month, most of conglomerate heads agreed to introduce
consolidated financial accounting and abolish the practice of
inter-subsidiary debt guarantees.
</P>
<P>
South Korea, once the 11th largest economy in the world, has
been in serious financial crisis caused by the collapse of some
conglomerates and bad loans of financial institutions late 1997.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement reached with the International Monetary Fund
last December for a bailout loan of 57 billion U.S. dollars, South
Korea has to restructure its ailing economy and completely open
its financial market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
