<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Criticizes U.S. Report on Human Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 6 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government
Friday criticized the United States for its recent report on human
rights in a number of developing countries like Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
"It is inconceivable that the United States feels privileged to
continue to systematically target a number of developing countries
like Indonesia as the violator of the human rights of their own
people," the Foreign Ministry said in a press release issued here
concerning a report by the U.S. State Department on human rights.
</P>
<P>
It charged that the United States does not only arrogate to
itself the right to patronize and pass judgment on another group
of countries which enjoy full right to an equal status, but it
also resorts to a false prism which is solely based on its own
experience when it seeks to judge situations completely different
from those affecting its own society.
</P>
<P>
The ministry described the report as reflecting an imbalanced
and biased view on the human rights situation in Indonesia,
containing misperceptions regarding the policies of the Indonesian
government and its conducts and being replete with inaccuracies.
</P>
<P>
It stressed that the protection, promotion and safeguarding of
human rights in Indonesia is and has always been a constitutional
imperative. "The very purpose of our national development is to
uplift the human dignity and integrity of all Indonesian
citizens."
</P>
<P>
The government of Indonesia, it said, also considers stability
to be critical to the continued political, social and economic
development of the country. The government will do everything
required to protect the freedom of all Indonesians and ensure that
there is an environment that enables all citizens to exercise
those rights.
</P>
<P>
Publication of imbalanced and self-righteous reports containing
inaccuracies, baseless accusations and heresies such as the State
Department's report will only hamper efforts to promote and
protect human rights and fundamental freedoms, it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
