<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swedish Government Decides to Begin Total Nuclear Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, February 6 (Xinhua) -- The Swedish government
formally decided Thursday to close the first of its 12 nuclear
power reactors, Barsebaeck 1 in southern Sweden by July 1.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made in accordance with the result of a 1980
referendum, in which Swedes voted in favor of a total nuclear
phase-out by 2010.
</P>
<P>
The decision triggered protests from opposition political
parties as well as Swedish electricity company Sydcraft, the
private owner of Barsebaeck 1 and Germany's Preussen Electra, the
main owner of Sydcraft.
</P>
<P>
"It will probably cost the state treasury at least 10 billion
Swedish kronor (1.25 billion U.S. dollars) at a time when health
care and the schools are crying out for more money," Liberal
Party criticized the decision by the Social Democratic government
in a comment.
</P>
<P>
Sydcraft holds that the government should start the nuclear ban
program with the state-owned power company Vattenfall.
</P>
<P>
The electricity supplied by all of Sweden's nuclear reactors
currently account for more than half of the country's power.
</P>
</TEXT>
