<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Specialists Refute U.S. Human Rights Report (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Zhu Muzhi, president of the China Society for Human Rights
Studies, said that although the report admitted that China has
made some progress in human rights, some of its content ignores
facts and justice.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said the country's greatest achievement in human rights has
been China's success in providing adequate food and clothing for
its 1.2 billion people and in helping more than 50 million people
rise above the poverty level.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the U.S. report denies the achievement as
progress in China's human rights, instead attributing that to a
condition for maintaining power by the Chinese Communist Party
(CPC). The report also states that 350 million Chinese people are
living in poverty.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said that the report only appears to take a fair stand in
its attacks on China.
</P>
<P>
For example, the report depicts China's jails as terrible
hells, he said. But the report also notes that when a delegation
of the United Nations Working Group on Arbitrary Detention visited
jails in Beijing, Shanghai, Chengdu and Xi'an, members of the
delegation were allowed to talk with prisoners without the
presence of a Chinese official, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
Some charges in the report that are applied to China also could
be applied to the United States, Zhu said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
