<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poisonous Fly Invades Kampala </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Nairobi Fly, a poisonous
insect, has invaded Kampala, a Chinese doctor confirmed here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
John Ekudu, the dean of Makerere University, reported to the
vector control division of the university and took samples of the
insect to the division. The division called the insect as
Nairobi Eye beetles.
</P>
<P>
The insect is described as a tiny red beetle with short
hard-wings. It spends most of the day time on the walls and
ceilings and is attracted at night to light.
</P>
<P>
The insect never bites nor stings but releases a poisonous
substance on human body that causes painful ugly swelling or tiny
blisters and sores on the skin. The victims' eyes may also swell
and discharge yellowish liquid.
</P>
<P>
Liu Jianhua, a doctor in Shanxi Hospital in the city, told
Xinhua that they treated quite several such cases since
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
Liu and other local medical staff said they have no ready cure
to the poison and they treated the patients with antibiotics and
drugs reducing the swellings.
</P>
<P>
There were no serious cases threatening the life of the
patients, and the victims generally recover within two weeks, Liu
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
