<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Actively Seeks Peaceful Settlement of Iraqi Crisis (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China is actively discussing ways to ease the crisis with all
relevant countries. Chinese vice-foreign ministers Li Zhaoxing and
Zhang Deguang, and Assistant Foreign Minister Ji Peiding, met
respectively with Russian Vice-Foreign Minister Grigori Karasin,
British Ambassador to China Anthony Charles Galsworthy and Saudi
Arabian Ambassador to China Al Madani.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side stressed that the current situation is rapidly
deteriorating and the crisis can only be solved through dialog and
cooperation, with a solution requiring all parties to exercise
wisdom and flexibility. The use of force or threat to use force
will only intensify contradictions rather than help to solve the
problems.
</P>
<P>
China maintains that Iraq should earnestly and comprehensively
implement all relevant UN Security Council resolutions, and should
fully cooperate with the UN by fulfiling its obligation to destroy
all weapons of mass destruction. Based on Iraq's implementation of
resolutions, the Security Council should gradually relax and
remove sanctions. China sincerly hopes that the United Nations
Special Commission will continue to engage in discussions and
dialog with Iraq in order to find a proper settlement which will
lead to the implementation of its work in line with Security
Council authorization. Related efforts should fully respect Iraq's
sovereignty and dignity and its concerns about security.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Ambassador to France Cai Fangbo told French leaders
that China is deeply concerned about the escalating situation
resulting from disputes over weapons inspections. And since early
this year, China has sent three experts to participate in the work
of inspection and will also send experts to attend the weapons
inspection appraisal meeting to be held in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
At present, the crisis in weapons insections is still in
escalation, and China will continue to play an active role in
seeking a peaceful settlement to the crisis, the article said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
