<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet's Economic Growth For 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, February 6 (Xinhua) -- The Tibet Autonomous Region's
economy grew at a faster rate than China's average last year and
had a GDP estimated at 7.35 billion yuan, an increase of 10
percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
According to an autonomous regional government official, Tibet
spent more than 400 million yuan on agriculture and livestock,
farmland, irrigation projects, Lhasa, Nyangqu, and Yarlung Zangbo
river development projects, and technology spread programs, in
1997.
</P>
<P>
Tibet had a good harvest for the tenth year in a row, with
820,000 tons of grain, up 5.5 percent from 1996, and 5.6 million
head of cattle, 19 percent of them sold.
</P>
<P>
Annual per capita income in rural areas last year was 1,040
yuan, an increase of 6.7 percent from 1996, and some 120,000
people in four poor counties got out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
Industrial output of the region in 1997 was about 1.22 billion
yuan, an increase of 14.5 percent over 1996. It now has five
enterprises listed on stock markets. Of them, two were listed in
1997.
</P>
<P>
Spending on key construction projects in the region last year
was 2.8 billion yuan. These included the Qinghai-Tibet and
Sichuan-Tibet highways, optical fiber cable projects linking
Lanzhou, the capital of northwestern Gansu province, Xining, the
capital of northwestern Qinghai province, and Lhasa, and mobile
phone systems in six cities.
</P>
<P>
Four generators at Yarzho Yumco Lake began trial operation, and
the region's annual generating capacity reached 300,000 kilowatts.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Imports and exports last year were worth 140 million
U.S. dollars, up 30 percent, and the service trade did 2.71
billion yuan worth of business, an increase of 16.4 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
