<BODY>
<HEADLINE> C. African Economic Community to Resume Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, February 6 (Xinhua) -- The Central African Economic
Community (CEEAC) is to resume operation after four years of
silence and becomes a tool in preserving regional stability and
development.
</P>
<P>
Franca Van-Dunem, the Angolan Prime Minister said here Friday
before his trip to Libreville, capital of Gabon, for the CEEAC
summit that the summit would see the regional organization
working. Van-Dunem attends the summit on behalf of Angolan
President Dos Santos,.
</P>
<P>
On the one-day meeting, Van-Dunem said a plan to revitalize
CEEAC will be mapped out so to make the regional organization
serve its original function.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the summit will also work out a budget for the
organization so that it could start working within this year.
</P>
<P>
The idea to re-start the organization was brought forward by
Angolan President Dos Santos on the four-sided meeting between
Gabon, Congo (K), Congo (B) and Angola in October last year.
</P>
<P>
CEEAC was established in October 1983 in Libreville. It was
made up by 11 countries such as Burundi, Equatorial Guinea, Congo
(B), Gabon, Cameroun, Rwanda, Sao Tome &AMP; Principe, Congo (K),
Chad, the Central African Republic and Angola.
</P>
<P>
But the regional economic organization came to a halt in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
