<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Official Stresses Sanitation Conditions For Hong Kong-Bound Chickens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, February 6 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese inland resumed
shipping live chickens to Hong Kong late today, with a government
official calling for more attention to the sanitation condition of
the livestocks.
</P>
<P>
"In shipping live domestic fowls and animals to Hong Kong,
overriding importance must be attached to safety and sanitation
conditions," Yu Dahai, China's leading official in charge of
quarantine of animals and plants, told reporters here today.
</P>
<P>
The quarantine departments must take responsibility for the
health of the Hong Kong residents, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Yu added that both the quarantine instruments and
methods of the Chinese inland have reached advanced world levels.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong suspended importing live chickens from the Chinese
inland in late December last year.
</P>
<P>
Yu said that the quantity of live chickens to be shipped to
Hong Kong, which averaged 100,000 each day before the outbreak of
a bird flu, will be dependent on the quarantine quality and the
responses of the Hong Kong people.
</P>
<P>
"We will not blindly raise the amount just in order to make
more foreign exchange, let alone slacken the requirements of
quarantine as time passes by," he said.
</P>
<P>
It may take a fairly long period of time for the Chinese inland
to restore its daily export of 100,000 live chickens to Hong Kong,
Yu said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
