<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Industrial Sales Increase in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Industrial sales for the first
10 months of 1997 in the Philippines reached 352.7 billion pesos
(8.8 billion U.S. dollars), up by 12 percent from the previous
year's 315.8 billion pesos (7.9 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
A survey released on Friday by the Department of Trade and
Industry Management Information Service showed that 12 sectors
experienced positive sales with value growth rates varying from 1
to 48 percent.
</P>
<P>
Garments posted the highest sales at 70.2 billion pesos (1.8
billion dollars) from 61.7 billion pesos (1.5 billion dollars)
with the peso depreciation primarily assuring the growth.
</P>
<P>
Electronics ranked second with 59.8 billion pesos (1.5 billion
dollars) though sales and value of the sector recorded a hefty
48-percent growth during the 10-month period.
</P>
<P>
This was due to the increase in global demand for integrated
circuits used in cellular phones and pagers, according to the
survey.
</P>
<P>
Food processing went up by 1 percent to 52.9 billion pesos (1.3
billion dollars) and consumer non-durables by 17 percent to 34.1
billion pesos (852.5 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The biggest loser in terms of value was sugar, with sales
plummeting by 67 percent from 1.7 billion pesos (42.5 million
dollars) to 542 million pesos (13.6 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The survey attributed this to the peso's fall which had
resulted in the lack of raw materials and the influx of imported
sugar onto the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
The next big loser was packaging materials, which saw a
20-percent drop from 4.1 billion pesos (10.3 million dollars) to
3.3 billion pesos (8.3 million dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
