<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Specialists Refute U.S. Human Rights Report (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tan Songqiu, executive councillor of the China Society for
Human Rights Studies, said the report has fabricated many cases to
attack China, most of which are distorted.
</P>
<P>
For example, he said, the report states that Catholic Church
Bishop Joseph Fan Zhongliang was arrested in his house in
Shanghai. Fan has stayed with his niece in Shanghai and has never
been arrested, Tan said.
</P>
<P>
In the report, Liu Fanwen was cited as a "dissident" and
"democratic activist." Liu's sentence to education through labor
was regarded as a proof of China's interference in human rights.
</P>
<P>
Tan said that Liu is not a democratic activist, but a hooligan
who harasses women. In 1982, Liu sexually harassed women on a bus
and was reprimanded by the Public Security Bureau of the Dongcheng
District in Beijing. In 1985, he also harassed women cleaners at
the toilets of Heizima and Nanluogu lanes in Beijing. In June of
1986, Liu gave himself up to the police and was exempted from
penalty, but in June of 1994 he was given a two-year
labor-education sentence for insulting women at Andingmen in
Beijing. On Feb. 25, 1997, Liu was sentenced to another two-year
term for his conduct with women.
</P>
<P>
Tan said that it is a pity that such a hooligan should be cited
in the report as one of the "radicals" to be protected by the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Hongyi, professor of Beijing Normal University, said that
as far as the human rights issue is concerned, the United States
has always adopted a double standard.
</P>
<P>
He said that the report accuses China of interfering in human
rights because "it does not tolerate religious manifestations that
advocate Tibetan independence or any expression of divisiveness."
</P>
<P>
Zhang said the report aims to support the Dalai Lama clique
which advocates independence.
</P>
<P>
But, he said, in the United States the U.S. Constitution aims
to set up an unbreakable federation of states which cannot be
separated from the union, and that any action to split the country
will be subject to stern legal penalties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
