<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Specialists Refute U.S. Human Rights Report (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dong Yunhu, a professor with the Party School of the CPC
Central Committee, said at the seminar that there are severe human
rights problems in the United States. Violent crimes are so
serious that 65 persons die each day of violence and that more
than 6,000 people are seriously maimed as a result of
violence. The mortality rate from violence in the United States is
10 times that in China.
</P>
<P>
During the past 10 years, the U.S. prison population increased
by a yearly average of 8.1 percent. In 1997 the number of
prisoners exceeded 1.7 million, or seven per 1,000 of the
U.S. population.
</P>
<P>
"Racial discrimination is well-rooted in the United States,"
Dong said. Blacks, who make up only 12 percent of the
U.S. population, account for more than half of all prisoners and
40 percent of those given the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
Facing similar charges, blacks are 10 times more likely to be
sentenced to death than whites. The poverty rate of black families
is 15 percent higher than whites, and the life expectancy of black
men is 7.5 years less than white males and 5.2 years less for
black women, Dong said.
</P>
<P>
"The United States, with such a bad human rights record,
mentions nothing about its own human rights problems, but distorts
the facts and attacks the human rights situation in other
countries," he said. "That is a typical double standard," he
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
According to Beijing University professor Tian Dan, the United
States has ulterior motives for targeting China for criticism. For
example, the report claims there is no freedom of speech in China
and that its people are prohibited from criticizing the
government. But, in fact, Tian said, China's newspapers,
periodicals and television often give critical reports and
comments on the defects of the work of government departments. The
opinions of the masses are fully expressed and not limited by the
government, Tian said.
</P>
<P>
What some Americans seem to want, Tian said, is the kind of
free speech which advocates the overthrow of the legitimate
government and the socialist system of China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Specialists Refute U.S. Human Rights Report (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tian Jin, executive council member of the United Nations
Association of China, said there is a diehard political force in
the United States which does not want China to remain a socialist
country and does not want to acknowledge China's stability,
development and progress.
</P>
<P>
"On the excuse of human rights, they give support to a very
small group of so-called dissidents in China who endanger national
security and go in for divisive activities, attempting to change
the nature of China's society and its path of development," the
professor said. "That will surely arouse the disgust and
opposition of the Chinese people," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zheng Hangsheng, a professor with the People's University of
China, said at the seminar that the United States advertises
itself as the embodiment of the universality of human rights and
gives itself the airs of an international human rights judge. In
that role, the United States treats other countries as the accused
and reprimands others which do not conform with, or consent to,
its human rights view and human rights model.
</P>
<P>
"This overbearing action shows its self-centeredness with
regard to human rights issues," Zheng said.
</P>
<P>
Huang Nansen, a professor with Beijing University, said that
the United States accounts for less than 5 percent of the world's
total population, but consumes 30 percent of the world's
petroleum, natural gas and coal.
</P>
<P>
"In accordance with such a standard, the 1.2 billion Chinese
would consume 120 percent of the world's total energy," he said.
</P>
<P>
The swelling of personal freedom in the United States has
resulted in an infringement on the freedom of others and even
personal safety. For example, he said, the freedom of
homosexuality leads to the spread of AIDS and other sexual
diseases, and the freedom of private gun ownership leads to
frequent violent and terrorist incidents in U.S. society.
</P>
<P>
"If such freedoms in the United States are introduced as
universal human rights around the world, the world will be plunged
into a mess," Huang said.
</P>
<P>
Liu Yizong, a professor with the Foreign Affairs College, said
that since Chinese President Jiang Zemin's visit to the United
States last year, Sino-U.S. relations have improved. The two
countries have decided to establish a strategic partnership toward
the 21st century and resolve differences with regard to human
rights on the basis of equality and mutual respect, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
"However, only several months after the visit, the U.S. State
Department overtly ran against the above-mentioned guidelines and
released its human rights report, attacking China's human rights
and creating confrontation purposely," Li said. "Obviously, it is
a move to poison the relations of the two countries."
</P>
<P>
Other participants at the seminar said that the United States
issues yearly human rights reports which provoke confrontations,
violate basic international norms and the current progressive tide
of the world, and meet resistance and opposition in more countries.
</P>
<P>
The participants said that if the United States really pays
attention to human rights, it should first improve its own
situation and halt its overbearing interference in the internal
affairs of other countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Calls to Fight Against Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 6 (Xinhua) -- President Nelson Mandela
Friday called on people of South Africa, especially the whites,
to offer voluntary community service to help end the crime
scourge and meet other socio-economic challenges.
</P>
<P>
In his address at the opening of parliament, Mandela said his
government could do more if every South African consciously asked
themselves everyday whether they might have assisted in the
commission of a crime.
</P>
<P>
Referring to crime, Mandela said most serious crime had
decreased since his government came into power in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Since 1994, there had been a marked decline in serious crimes
such as murder, robbery, taxi violence and car-hijacking, which,
Mandela said, were the result of better co-ordination among the
security services.
</P>
<P>
Mandela disagreed on the saying that crime situation had been
worsening, noting that there was a tendency to exaggerate and
distort the real crime situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, however, said particular attention would this year be
paid to woman and child abuse -- crimes which were on the
increase.
</P>
<P>
Renewing his new patriotism call, Mandela urged South Africans
to build the nation into "a community of citizens who appreciate
their civil duty".
</P>
<P>
He defended his government's performance since coming into
power, stressing that it had met, and in some instance even
surpassed last year's targets.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said his government remained committed to meeting its
budget deficit target. The government would strive creatively to
meet its obligations within the context of a reduction in the
public debt, he said, adding: "we must eliminate overspending."
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Mandela also pledged to continue the
government's efforts to improve the majority of people's living
and working condition. He said affirmative action was the only
way of moving away from racial discrimination to true equality.
</P>
<P>
He said although the government might not meet its election
promise of one million houses in five years, it would do its best
to meet the target. He said, "whatever the difficulties... we are
on course to ensure that in the end there shall be housing and
security for all."
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, 1,000 houses are being
started or completed very two-and-a-half days, and as a result of
government programs 1.2 million more South Africans had a
permanent roof over their heads.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Mandela government's targets for 1998
included ensuring that 90 percent of mothers and children had
access to free medical care, that a further 580,000 telephones
would be installed, and a further one million citizens supplied
with clean and accessible water.
</P>
<P>
As a measure to improve good governance, his office would also
begin drafting legislation on ethics in government. This would
include a statutory code of conduct for members of the executive
at national and provincial level, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
