<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, February 6 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's incoming prime
minister said here Friday that his country will never develop
official relations with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Kim Jong-pil, the honorary president of the United Liberal
Democrats, will become the prime minister of a coalition
government late this month under an agreement reached between his
party and the National Congress for New Politics led by
President-elect Kin Dae-jung.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Chinese correspondents ahead of
his visit to China Sunday, Kim Jong-pil said that South Korea will
strictly keep its promise on the Taiwan issue as specified in the
joint communique signed by South Korea and China on August 24,
1992 for establishing full diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
He said that the issue of Taiwan is an internal affair of China
and that South Korea's contacts with Taiwan will continue to be
restricted to non-governmental level.
</P>
<P>
Kim, a veteran South Korean statesman, will pay a four-day
visit to China at the invitation of the Communist Party of China.
</P>
<P>
He said that he has a very good impression of China although he
has never visited the country.
</P>
<P>
He said that his forthcoming visit is aimed at exchanging views
with Chinese leaders on various issues and enhancing mutual
understanding, friendship and cooperation between the two
countries. 
</P>
