<HEADLINE> India Loses Forests in Last Three Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, February 6 (Xinhua) -- India has lost about 5,500
square kilometers of forest cover in the last three years, said
the latest "State of the Forest Report -- 1997" released here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Though open forests increased by 12,001 square kilometers and
mangroves by 294 square kilometers, 17,777 square kilometers of
dense forests have been depleted since the last assessment in
1995.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Environment and Forests Saifuddin Soz in his press
conference here Friday called forests the real vitality of India.
He said a high-level committee including the Forest Survey of
India, various institutes, scientists and environmentalists has
been set up to formulate a long-term policy on the exploitation of
minerals in forests.
</P>
<P>
Madhya Pradesh in the central India has recorded the maximum
loss of 3,969 square kilometers of forests, followed by Andhra
Pradesh, which lost 3,294 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
This is the sixth assessment of the status of Indian forests,
based on visual and digital interpretation of satellite data.
</P>
</TEXT>
