<HEADLINE> Qian Qichen Meets Russian Deputy Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen reiterated today that China fully
supports a diplomatic solution to crisis in Iraq, and is opposed
to the use of military force.
</P>
<P>
Qian made the remarks during an afternoon meeting with Russian
Deputy Foreign Minister Grigori Karasin.
</P>
<P>
He said the pressing task at the moment is that all parties
concerned should persist in diplomatic efforts in order to solve
the crisis in a manner acceptable to all sides.
</P>
<P>
Qian expressed appreciation for Russia's active efforts to find
a peaceful solution to the crisis. He reiterated that China maintains
all relevant United Nations Security Council resolutions on the
Iraq issue should be earnestly implemented in a comprehensive
manner. He stressed that Iraq should cooperate fully with the UN
Special Commission (UNSCOM) and seriously implement its
obligations.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council should take steps to remove sanctions in
accordance with the development of how Iraq implements related
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM is operating with the support of the international
community and has made effective progress, said Qian, adding that
the commission should make timely objective assessments of certain
cases requiring no further investigation. UNSCOM should accelerate
efforts to avoid unnecessarily prolonging the investigation.
</P>
<P>
Qian pointed to the positiveness of Sino-Russian relations over
the past year, and noted that the two nations witnessed smooth
progress in the development of political ties. He said the two
nations signed several joint statements, completed demarcation of
the eastern section of Sino-Russian border, and enjoyed good
cooperation in the realm of international affairs.
</P>
<P>
Qian said China and Russia have broad prospects for mutually
beneficial cooperation and vast potential for trade. He added that
the two sides should engage in mutually beneficial development.
</P>
<P>
Karasin briefed Qian on Russia's diplomatic efforts to find a
workable solution to the crisis in Iraq. He said Russia and China
share many common views on the issue and expressed hope for
continued close contact.
</P>
<P>
Karasin arrived in China on Tuesday to join in consultations
between deputy foreign ministers from the two countries. The
Russian leader, who is visiting at the invitation of the Chinese
Foreign Ministry, also held talks with his Chinese counterpart,
Zhang Deguang, on promoting the development of bilateral
ties and various other major international issues of common
concern.  
</P>
</TEXT>
