<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Senate Ratifies New Oil Deregulation Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 6 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Senate Friday
ratified a bicameral conference committee report on the new Oil
Deregulation Bill, setting a uniform tariff of 3 percent for
imported crude and refined oil products.
</P>
<P>
The measure, which seeks to replace the old oil deregulation
law, also sets a 2.9 billion peso (72.5 million U.S. dollars)
buffer fund to subsidize oil companies during a five-month
transition period for full deregulation.
</P>
<P>
The old oil deregulation law, which took effect in February
1997, was nullified by the Supreme Court last November on the
grounds that it violated the country's constitution and the rule
of free trade.
</P>
<P>
The law provided for a 7-percent tariff for refined petroleum
products and a 3-percent tariff for crude oil to encourage firms
to invest in the domestic refining industry.
</P>
<P>
But the court ruled that free trade would be hindered if oil
firms were forced to choose between investing huge amounts in
refineries and paying higher tariffs.
</P>
<P>
Under the new bill, the full deregulation of the downstream oil
industry involving such socially-sensitive products as liquefied
petroleum gas, kerosene and gasoline shall come no less than five
months after the measure is signed into law.
</P>
<P>
But in other products, the bill empowers the president to
accelerate full deregulation upon the recommendation of the
Department of Energy and the Department of Finance.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, full deregulation may only be accelerated when
the prices of crude oil and petroleum products in the world market
are declining and the value of the peso in relation to the U.S.
dollar is stable.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
