<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Cuts Armed Forces by 7 million in 49 years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 6 (Xinhua) -- China has reduced its armed
forces by seven million since the founding of new China in 1949,
according to a senior officer of the People's Liberation Army
(PLA).
</P>
<P>
He said that China's latest disarmament was initiated following
a 1997 September announcement by Jiang Zemin, chairman of the
Central Military Commission, that the PLA would further reduce its
forces by 500,000 personnel over the next three years, marking the
ninth cut of the country's armed forces in 49 years.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made the announcement during 15th National Congress of
the Communist Party of China held last September 12-18.
</P>
<P>
A number of field troops from the PLA Group Army have been
transfered to armed police units during the current ongoing ninth
round of military disarmament.
</P>
<P>
China's first armed forces cut was launched at the end of 1950
with a 17.1 percent reduction in a force of 5.5 million personnel.
</P>
<P>
The number of PLA personnel jumped to a record 6.1 million in
1951 during the War to Resist U.S. Aggression and Aid Korea.
</P>
<P>
China's second round of disarmament was carried out in January
1952 when the total number of PLA personnel fell to around 3
million. Staff levels at the PLA headquarters and departments at
various other levels were reduced by at least one third, with
local units integrated into public security departments, and a
large number of staffers entering military universities.
</P>
<P>
The third round of disarmament in 1953 was followed by the
fourth round in 1957. The former round involved a 23.3 percent cut
of the total troops, with the latter round resulting in a 33
percent reduction.
</P>
<P>
The fifth round was characterized by significant reductions in
the infantry, engineering and railway corps.
</P>
<P>
The sixth, seventh and eighth cuts were in 1978, 1980 and 1985
with the eighth cut being one million, a record reduction in the
history of the PLA.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hutu Militiamen Kill 34 in Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Hutu militia massacred 34
people Wednesday night in Rwanda's Jenda settlement, which is
located on the border between Ruhengeri and Gisenyi Prefectures,
officials in Ruhengeri said.
</P>
<P>
The Rwanda News Agency (RNA) quoted Boniface Rucagu, prefect
of Ruhengeri as saying that a large group of militiamen armed
with guns, machetes, axes and clubs killed 30 on the spot, and
critically wounded 13 others. One deaf person was abducted, he
said.
</P>
<P>
In a special dispatch to Xinhua, the RNA said during the
attack which occurred at around 8:00 p.m. local time, some of the
militiamen blocked the Ruhengeri-Gisenyi road, while others were
busy indiscriminately killing residents.
</P>
<P>
The victims are said to have been hacked to death by the
marauding Hutu extremists. "No single bullet was used," Rucagu
quoted survivors of the attack as saying.
</P>
<P>
"In addition to the 30 residents who died on the spot, three
of the wounded died later, and the deaf man was later found
dead," Rucagu added.
</P>
<P>
It is said that after the massacre, the killers withdrew back
to nearby forests.
</P>
<P>
Nearly one million Tutsis and moderate Hutus were killed by
Hutu government forces and militiamen in 1994 after a plane of
the then Rwandan president was downed over Kigali, killing him
and several ministers. This incident triggered off the Rwanda
genocide, and resulted in the assuming power of the present
regime in Kigali. 
</P>
</TEXT>
