<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Actively Seeks Peaceful Settlement of Iraqi Crisis (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 6 (Xinhua) -- An article signed by Guo Yali
and released today calls for active efforts to seek a peaceful
settlement to the ongoing crisis in Iraqi and states that China
will continue to play an influential role in reaching the goal.
</P>
<P>
The article notes that China, a permanent member of the United
Nations Security Council, has from the very beginning called on
the parties concerned to seek peaceful settlement to the dispute
over weapons inspection by engaging in dialogue and cooperation
and will continue supporting diplomatic efforts by all countries
in this regard.
</P>
<P>
In recent meetings with visiting British and French foreign
ministers, Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen
underlined that China is deeply concerned about the accelerating
deterioration of the crisis, and expressed the hope that
settlement of the issue will be accomplished through diplomatic
channels. China is opposed to both threats to use force and the
actual use of force. In a telephone conversation with
U.S. Secretary of State Madeline Albright and in messages to Iraqi
Vice-Prime Minister Tareq Aziz, Qian called for all concerned
parties to adopt a flexible attitude and practice restraint in
order to avoid further escalation of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Qin Huasen, China's representative to the UN,
pointed to UN Security Council deliberations of the Iraqi issue
and noted that China has consistently maintained that Iraq should
comprehensively implement the relevant resolutions adopted by the
council and fully cooperate with the UN Special Commission
(UNSCOM). However, he added, Iraq is a sovereign nation and the
international community should pay due attention to that country's
concerns about its dignity and sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
The article went on to say that the Iraq crisis is quite
obviously intensifying, with the U.S. deploying a huge military
force to the Gulf and Iraq escalating preparations for a possible
war.
</P>
<P>
China places high value on the forthcoming technical appraisal
of weapons inspections in Iraq and sincerely hopes that all
parties concerned will adopt an earnest attitude to avoid
irresponsible assertions and judgments so as to enable all the
participating experts to make an objective judgment concerning
Iraq's implementation of relevant UN Security resolutions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
