<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Inland Resuming Chicken Supply to Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, February 6 (Xinhua) -- The first batch of 38,000
live chicken will be shipped to Hong Kong from Shenzhen this
evening after going through rigid quarantine procedures.
</P>
<P>
The chickens are expected to be transported to various
wholesale markets of Hong Kong and be sold at local retail booths
tomorrow afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Technicians of Guangdong Provincial Department of Animal and
Plant Quarantine (GPDAPQ) were sent to 25 export-oriented chicken
farms in Guangzhou, dongguan, Zhuhai and Shenzhen cities yesterday
to collect chicken blood samples.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 blood samples were collected randomly from every
3,000 live chickens, doubling the amount required by the
Agriculture and Fisheries Department (AFD) of Hong Kong, said
Huang Weiming, deputy director of GPDAPQ.
</P>
<P>
The whole process was under the guidance and supervision of Yu
Dahai, director of the Chinese Administration of Animal and Plant
Quarantine under the Ministry of Agriculture and officials from
relevant departments in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Hong Kong AFD will send quarantine officials
to re-examine the result by random before the chicken are shipped
into Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, quarantine departments in Guangdong collected 11,000
blood samples from 200 poultry farms for test of H5N1
virus. Negative reaction was shown in all blood samples, Huang
said.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong will take new measures to examine H5N1 virus and
enhance quarantine management, Huang said.
</P>
<P>
Export of chicken from China's inland to Hong Kong was
temporarily suspended as a precautionary measure since December 23
because of the outbreak of bird flue in Hong Kong late last year.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
