<HEADLINE> 3 Million Ethiopian Farmers Benefit from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, February 6 (Xinhua) -- About 3 million Ethiopian
farmers have benifited from the implementation of extension
packages which also focused on development of cash crops, said
Ethiopian Minister of Agriculture Seifu Ketema.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the House of People's Representatives
Thursday, the minister said 989,000 farmers have been direct
beneficiaries of the extension programs in 1997 which shows a
rise by 53 percent from the set target for the year.
</P>
<P>
The number of farmers incorporated in leguminous and stalk
crops as well as fodder development packages has reached 375,000,
he said.
</P>
<P>
New packages on animal husbandry have also been prepared and
implemented in the stated period, he noted.
</P>
<P>
According to Ketema, the commitment the peasants have
displayed in applying the new technologies even in the face of
climate change is a testimony to their determination to carry on
with the programs.
</P>
<P>
The boost in agricultural production witnessed over the past
two years indicates that the country has the capability to be
self-sufficient in food, he added.
</P>
<P>
To attain self-sufficiency in food set by the five-year
development plan (1995-2000), the Ethiopian government organized
farmers in extension programs to teach peasants new farming
technologies and provide them with fertilizers and seeds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
