<HEADLINE> 1998 Is Year of Science, Technology for S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 6 (Xinhua) -- South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki said South African has attached great
importance to the development of science and technology in the
country, saying 1998 is the year of science and technology for
all South Africans.
</P>
<P>
Launching the Year of Science and Technology program, Mbeki
cited a 1996 world report on competitiveness, which showed South
Africa as being at the bottom of a 40-country list in the area of
human resources development for science, engineering and
technology.
</P>
<P>
"During this Year of Science and Technology..., the key
message must be that science, engineering and technology are
important for the survival of our country in an increasingly
competitive world," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Economic expansion on one side, and advances in science,
engineering and technology on the other, can hardly be seen
apart," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The attainment of a better life for all was dependent on South
Africans' achieving a competitive, growing and sustainable
economy, in which everyone participated, he noted.
</P>
<P>
For the first time the government was putting in place a
program to bring all South Africans into science, engineering and
technology, said Mbeki, who is patron of the program.
</P>
<P>
Lionel Mtshali, Minister of Arts, Culture, Science and
Technology, said the main reason for declaring 1998 the year of
science and technology was the results of two international
studies that rated South Africa "very poorly" in science,
engineering and technology and innovation.
</P>
<P>
Mtshali said his department, together with the science,
engineering and technology community, were working together "to
ensure that in 1998 South Africa would be in for a fascinating
and captivating experience of science, engineering and
technology". 
</P>
</TEXT>
