<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Leaders Appeal for Lifting of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Five African presidents Thursday
addressed an urgent appeal for the lifting of the international
embargo imposed against Libya since 1992.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was made by presidents from Sudan, Chad, Nigeria,
Mali and Libya at the end of their summit held in Libyan capital
of Tripoli. Tunisia, Egypt and Burkina Faso also sent delegates
to the summit.
</P>
<P>
The summit communique carried by the Libyan news agency called
for the immediate lifting of the sanctions against Libya in
conformity with the related resolutions of the Organization of
African Unity, the Arab League, the Organization of Islamic
Conference and the Non-Aligned Movement.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions were imposed after Libya refused to hand over two
suspects allegedly responsible for the bombing of a Pan Am jet
over Scotland in 1998, which killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
The leaders also signed a treaty for the establishment of a
group for consultations and action among the coastal, desert
African countries which confront similar internal and external
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
These countries will cooperate with each other in tapping the
rich human and natural resources in the coastal and desert areas
for the good of their development.
</P>
<P>
The newly founded framework will have a council of heads of
state, an executive council, a secretariat, a development bank and
an economic, social and cultural council. The secretariat will be
temporarily based in Tripoli. And the summit chose Libyan leader
Muammar Gaddafi as chairman of the current session of the council
of heads of state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
