<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Zoologists Try to Inseminate Cheetahs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 6 (Xinhua) -- South African zoologists have
artificially inseminated three cheetahs in hope to save the extremely
endangered animal, South African Press Association (SAPA) reported on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
If the cheetahs carry their cubs full term, it will be the first
successful artificial insemination of cheetahs in Africa, National
Zoological Gardens chief veterianarian Ian Espie was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Espie said five cheetahs, including four king cheetahs, were
selected for insemination, but only three were found to be ovulating
when they were examined on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The females had been injected twice with hormones to synchronize
and induce ovulation. A second injection was given to them on Tuesday.
Semen was extracted from male cheetah and injected into the ovulation
females.
</P>
<P>
If Thursday's procedure is successful, the three females will
give birth after the average gestation period of 93 days. Cheetah
usually give birth to two or four cubs at a time.
</P>
<P>
According to Espie, United States zoos had a 50 percent success
rate in cheetah insemination. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
