<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Weaker as Gold falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 6 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar finished
lower Friday in Sydney against the U.S. dollar after becoming
stalled in a narrow range.
</P>
<P>
The local unit finished at 67.58 U.S. cents, down from 67.83
previously.
</P>
<P>
Adding also to the softness in the market was softness in some
Asian currencies and of week position squaring by market
participants.
</P>
<P>
Overnight, the Australian dollar had rallied to a high of 68.43
U.S. cents as the price of gold rose.
</P>
<P>
But it eased off a little into the local open, as gold erased
all its gains to finish in New York around 299.50 U.S. dollars per
ounce, down 50 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
"It just shows how sensitive we are" currently to commodity
price movement, Macquarie Bank Foreign Exchange Manager Mark
O'Leary said earlier Friday.
</P>
<P>
Locally, gold closed weaker at 298.25 U.S. dollars per ounce.
</P>
<P>
Separately, the Australian dollar ended at 83.87 Japanese yen,
from 84.07 previously, and at 1.2086 German marks, from 1.2231.
</P>
