<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 10 Million Nigerians Suffer from River Blindness: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 6 (Xinhua) -- About 10 million Nigerians have
been infected with the river blindness disease, otherwise known
as onchocerciasis, and 150,000 of them are currently irreversibly
blind.
</P>
<P>
The startling revelation was made on Thursday by Emmanuel
Gemade, United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) project officer
for health in Nigeria, to herald the forthcoming National
Onchocerciasis Week taking place between February 8 and 13 in the
capital Abuja.
</P>
<P>
He also revealed that over 30 million Nigerians are at risk of
contracting the disease, since it has spread to over 30 states of
the federation, thus making the country the worst victim of river
blindness globally.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has a population of about 100 million.
</P>
<P>
According to Gemade, a United States-based company has
promised to supply free of charge the potent drug for fighting
the ailment (mectizan) until the scourge is totally eradicated
from the continent.
</P>
<P>
The African Program for Onchocerciasis Control, the United
Nations agency responsible for the fight against the disease in
African countries, has mapped out strategies to address the
issue, Gemade said.
</P>
<P>
One of the measures involves the use of members of the
communities involved as distributors of the drug.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, 12 million Nigerians had received the
drug, compared to the less than one million people that benefited
from the drug distribution program at its beginning of 1991.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 11:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Hopes for Peaceful Solution to Iraqi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu expressed the hope Friday for a peaceful
solution to the current Iraqi crisis, but adding Israel reserves
the right of self-defense if attacked.
</P>
<P>
In an official briefing on the Persian Gulf situation held
here to foreign diplomats based in Israel, Netanyahu said Israel
is "hopeful that there will be a peaceful solution to the present
crisis."
</P>
<P>
He voiced Israel's full support to the United States and the
international community in demanding Iraq to allow unfettered
search by U.N. inspectors of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said Israel is exercising a policy of restraint and
responsibility over the Iraqi crisis so to avoid getting involved
in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
He said Israel's assessment is that "the risk of Iraq
attacking Israel is low, even very low," but stressing Israel's
right of self-defense against any such attack. "We reserve the
right of self-defense, which is a natural right of any state, or
nation, under potential real attacks," he said.
</P>
<P>
In the past days, Israeli leaders have been trying to
allay fears among its citizens about a possible Iraqi biological
and chemical attack. The U.S., who is wielding the option of
a military strike against Iraq, has reportedly urged Israel to
refrain from retaliating if attacked by Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In the 1991 Gulf War, Israel was forced by Washington to
refrain from striking back when Iraq launched dozens of Scud
missiles against it. But most Israeli politicians maintained this
time that if attacked again, Israel would not stay idle and would
retaliate according to its own security interests.
</P>
<P>
Besides the danger of Iraq, Netanyahu tried to draw
international attention to the same efforts that Iran is making
to acquire ballistic missiles and non-conventional weapons.
</P>
<P>
He urged the international community to pay equal attention to
the Iranian efforts, which he called as another major source of
instability in Middle East. He warned that if Iran continues to
develop its weapons programs unimpeded, it would pose threats not
only to the region, but to the world as a whole. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
