<HEADLINE> Somali Warlord Pledges Quick Withdrawal From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 6 (Xinhua)--Somali warlord Hussein Mohamed
Aideed has agreed to withdraw his militiamen out of the southern
town of Baidoa, ahead of a peace conference due to open on
February 15, said a report reaching here Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We shall respect all genuine agreements regarding the
pacification of the twon," said Aideed's spokesman Abikar Qali.
</P>
<P>
The withdrawal will comply with an undertaking Mr. Aideed gave
at a peace conference ended in Cairo on December 22. The
conference ended with an agreeement by 26 factional leaders to
meet in Baidoa to establish a federal state and an interim
government.
</P>
<P>
Baidoa was captured by Mr. Aideed's father, the late General
Mohamed Farah Aideed, in September 1995 from the Rahanwein Clan.
</P>
<P>
"Our troops will be deployed outside Baidoa according to the
Cairo agreement," Qali said.
</P>
<P>
But the Rahanwein Resitance Army (RRA) spokesman Mohamed Aden
Qalinle said he did not believe Aideed's troops withdrawal would
take place.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Somalia's main warlords Mr. Aideed, Mr. Mahdi and
Osman Hassan Ali Atto, had agreed on January 31 to take away the
barricades and checkpoints that have divided the capital
Mogadishu into three zones in the past seven years, and reopen
both port and airport in the capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
