<HEADLINE> Partial Curfew Imposed in Kenya's Nakuru District </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's Nakuru District has been
placed under a partial curfew from Thursday evening, closing all
business premises in urban centers between 9 p.m. and 6 a.m.
until the security situation returns to normal.
</P>
<P>
The curfew was declared by Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
Thursday when he received in Nakuru, about 165 kilometers
northwest of Nairobi, a delegation of leaders from all
communities of the district, local press reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The president told the delegation that a prominent councillor
of opposition Democratic Party (DP) and other opposition
councillors in Nakuru were funding the on-going violence in Njoro
and laikipia areas.
</P>
<P>
He noted that opposition leaders behind the violence wanted to
plunge the country into an arena of genocide like the one
witnessed in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
Moi said that anyone found loitering in urban centers in the
district after 9 p.m. would be arrested and anyone calling on
people to arm themselves should be arrested and punished.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan Head of State instructed the Rift Valley provincial
Security Committee and the Nakuru District Security Committee to
deploy security personnel, both uniformed and ununiformed, in the
clash areas.
</P>
<P>
Opposition Democratic Party of Kenya (DP) Chairman Mwai Kibaki
Thursday denied an allegation that his party was behind a plot to
topple the government.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, 42 Rift Valley MPs from the ruling Kenya African
National Union (KANU) implicated DP in a plot aimed at bringing
down the KANU government through killings and clashes.
</P>
<P>
Nakuru District is one of the 17 districts of Rift Valley
Province with a population of over 300,000 and Nakuru town is the
capital of the province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
