<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Govt Warns Against New Price Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 6 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government has
ordered bakers and cooking oil manufacturers to stop any further
increase of bread and cooking oil prices.
</P>
<P>
"The government will hold the prices at present levels and
hold further meetings with the manufacturers to see if they can
even be brought down," said Nathan Shamuyarira, Minister of
Industry and Commerce on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the government and millers have
agreed to hold the price of maize meal at present levels for
three months, while bakers agreed to suspend a 25 percent
increase in bread prices and oil producers have been asked to
forgo a 20.5 percent proposed increase.
</P>
<P>
"Generally what the government is trying to do is to hold the
prices for all basic commodities as what they are for some time
while we try to find a solution to the problem of sharp price
increases," he said.
</P>
<P>
A task force was set up by the government to review price
increases following last month's alarming price increases of
essential goods which triggered violent food riots.
</P>
<P>
From January 19 to 21, thousands of residents in the capital
Harare and other towns staged the demonstrations in protest
against the steep prices increases. Some of them looted shops,
stoned cars and destroyed properties, causing million of Dollars
losses.
</P>
<P>
The minister assured the nation that the government had enough
maize in stock to see the country through the next four months at
the current consumption rate of 50,000 tons a month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
