<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weakening Asian Currencies Attractive to U.S. Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, February 5 (Xinhua) -- Amid the current Asian
financial crisis, travel agencies in the United States received a
lot more phone calls than usual, asking information about travels
to the region.
</P>
<P>
One of them, based in San Diego, said that since it slashed its
tour prices to Asia late last month, incoming phone calls have
more than doubled.
</P>
<P>
"People from all over North America have decided that now is a
good time to visit Asia," a marketing executive of the Japan
Orient Tours said.
</P>
<P>
At Japan Orient Tours, tickest from Los Angeles to Hong Kong,
including round air fare and a five-night hotel stay, were slashed
from 1,298 U.S. dollars to 798 dollars.
</P>
<P>
At Balboa Travel, the price of a round-trip package with three
night-stay in Tokyo also dropped by a third, from 1,498 dollars to
988 dollars. Fares to Bangkok, Hong Kong and Indonesia dropped 300
U.S. dollars to 500 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to tourism analysts, the drop-off price is also
caused by the sharp decline in business travels. Fewer executives
from Japan, Hong Kong and South Korea take business trips.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, there are fewer travelers to the United States, from
Asia, especially from Japan and South Korea. Local tourism
analysts predict that Japan's economic problems will cut further
into Japanese tourists' spending patterns.
</P>
<P>
According Joe McInerney, CEO of the Pacific Asia Travel
Association (PATA), South Pacific members are also feeling the
impact of the economic situation in Asia. McInerney has just
returned from a recent visit to Australis, New Zealand and Fiji,
</P>
<P>
Roundtable meetings with industry leaders and PATA members are
being scheduled for a number of Northeast Asian locations in
Mid-February, PATA said. McInerney will conduct sessions in Tokyo,
Osaka, Seoul, Beijing and Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
