<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic Torch Arrives in Nagano </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Three Olympic torches which
have been relayed throughout Japan in the past month reunified here on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
At a torch reunification ceremony in Central Square, Nagano city,
former Olympic champions passed the torches to the president of the
Nagano Organizing Committee president Eishiro Saito, Governor of
Nagano Goro Yoshimura and Mayor of Nagano City Tasuku Tsukada
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The flame was kindled at the Temple of Hera in Olympia, Greece on
December 19 last year and arrived in Japan on December 23.
</P>
<P>
From January 6, 1998, the Torch Relay within Japan began in three
separate and simultaneous routes, covering 47 prefectures in the
country.
</P>
<P>
On January 23, the three flames arrived in Nagano Prefecture where
runners subsequently carried them through all 120 cities, towns, and
villages.
</P>
<P>
The final lap of the three routes were carried by Albertville
women's figure skating champion Kristi Yamaguchi, 1964 Olympics
women's volleyball gold medal team member Masae Nakamura and Atlanta
Olympics judo champion Yuko Emoto.
</P>
<P>
The flame will be kept in a safety place until Saturday when it is
used to ignite the cauldron of the winter games.
</P>
<P>
At the reunification ceremony, International Olympic Committee
president Juan Antonio Samaranch said:"The Olympic flame represents
the spirit of the Olympic Games. The Olympic flame is a symbol of
peace and hope. It reminds us that by working together we can build a
peaceful and better world." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
