<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> California's Two Top Banks to Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, February 5 (Xinhua) -- Two of California's largest
banks - Los Angeles' Glendale Federal Bank and San Francisco's
California Federal Bank - will merge into the third largest
savings and loans in the United States, reports from both banks
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The goal of the merger is to grab a leading share of deposits
in key markest such as Los Angeles, San Francisco, San Diego and
Orange County where both banks competed each other in the past,
said Gerald J. Ford, chairman and chief executive of California
Federal Bank.
</P>
<P>
Some branches will close in neighborhoods where both banks have
offices, he said, adding that it would cut costs by 131 million
U.S. dollars following the merger.
</P>
<P>
Glendale Federal Bank is the sixth-largest thrift in California
with 16 billion U.S. dollars in assets, 181 banking offices and 26
loan offices in the state.
</P>
<P>
California Federal Bank is the fourth-largest thrift with more
than 30 billion U.S. dollars in assets, 225 branches, including
194 in California, 24 in Florida and seven in Nevada.
</P>
<P>
The merged institution will be called California Federal Bank
and based in San Francisco. It will have more than 400 branches
with 51 billion U.S. dollars in assets, 6.4 percent of the
California's deposits.
</P>
<P>
The boards of directors of both banks have approved the
transaction, but it still needs regulatory and shareholder
approval.
</P>
<P>
The deal is expected to close in the third quarter of this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
