<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supercomputers in India Not to Be Affected by US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, February 6 (Xinhua) -- India's noted supercomputer
expert V. Rajaraman said Friday that the United States' move to
promulgate a new regulation to permanently peek into all end-users
of U.S.-made supercomputers in India will not have any tangible
effect on the country as it has developed its own supercomputers.
</P>
<P>
Unlike the 1980s when the supercomputer was denied to the
Indian Institute of Science in Bangalore, a new emerged industrial
city 2019 km south of New Delhi, the move would not produce any
tangible effect this time, said Rajaraman, founder chairman of the
Supercomputer Education and Research Center.
</P>
<P>
The regulation is irrelevant as far as India is concerned, said
Rajaraman, when asked about the possible impact of the move on the
country's ongoing defense, space and nuclear programs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
