<HEADLINE> Nigeria Tells West Not to Meddle in Other's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria stressed on Thursday the
need for western countries to eschew what it termed "meddlesomeness"
in its national business.
</P>
<P>
Mutual respect for the sovereign rights of countries could
heal the wounds of distrust and muscle-flexing which currently
pervades the circle of international diplomacy, said Alhaji
Buhari Bala, Nigerian Minister of State for Foreign Affairs.
</P>
<P>
The minister's remarks, according to the Guardian newspaper
today, is apparently a response to the censure on alleged human
rights abuses in Nigeria by the United States.
</P>
<P>
In a report titled "Nigeria Country Report On Human Rights
Practices For 1997", the U.S. described the scorecard of the
Nigerian government in this respect as "dismal" last year.
</P>
<P>
It claimed that despite the announcement of a timetable for
transition from military to multi-party rule, "there was little
meaningful progress toward democracy".
</P>
<P>
It also found fault with Nigeria's local government elections
last March although the polls "were largely peaceful" and called
for release of political detainees.
</P>
<P>
However, the minister, at a meeting with Tunisian ambassador
to Nigeria, said the on-going transition to civil rule program
could not be doubted any longer while the country's doors "will
remain open on constructive dialogue, economic and cultural
issues".
</P>
<P>
According to the timetable, an elected government will take
over power from the military on October 1 this year. Preparations
for the elections of the National Assembly, state governors and
president are underway.
</P>
<P>
The National Electoral Commission of Nigeria on Thursday
released details of delineated federal constituencies and
senatorial districts across the 36 states and the federal capital
territory for the April 25 national assembly elections.
</P>
<P>
Elections of governors and president will be held in August.
</P>
</TEXT>
