<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Caspian Oil Pipeline to Cost 2.5 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 6 (Xinhua) -- An international pipeline to
transfer Caspian oil to the European markets will cost 2.5 billion
U.S. dollars, according to a feasibility study.
</P>
<P>
Starting from Baku, Azerbaijan and ending in the southern
Turkish port of Ceyhan, the pipeline will have 468 kilometers in
Azerbaijan, 225 kilometers in Georgia and 1,037 kilometers in
Turkey, according to the study report available Friday.
</P>
<P>
If completed, the pipeline is expected to have a capacity of 45
million tonnes per year and the figure could be raised in the
future, said study report, which was prepared by a german expert
team and financed by the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Engery and Natural Resources Minister Cumhur Ersumer
told reporters here Thursday that choosing this land route could
reduce the pressure on the Turkish Straits whose waters have been
suffering increasing pollution of oil tankers sailing through it.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that Turkey also will take advantage of
the pipeline by collecting transportation fees and buying crude
oil at a lower price when it is put into operation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ersumer stated that Russian oil could also be
carried by this pipeline, saying Turkey welcomes Russian companies
to join in the project.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been playing an active role in exploiting the
abundant Caspian area in order to meet its rapidly increasing
energy demands.
</P>
<P>
As an oil-starving country, Turkey has to import oil and
natural gas from its neighboring countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
