<HEADLINE> Share Prices Sharply Higher on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Share prices rose sharply in
record trading on the Singapore market as the benchmark Straits
Times Industrials Index (STII) surged by 44.76 points to close at
1536.91 points on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that Malaysian stocks continued to dominate trade
with penny stocks hitching a ride as well. "It was another day for
investors to buy up laggards, including SESDAQ (Stock Exchange of
Singapore Dealing and Automated Quotation System) stocks," one
dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Reflecting the upbeat sentiment, the properties index ended up
by 10.55 points, or about three percent, as retail and
institutional investors continued buying, they noted.
</P>
<P>
Total market volume reached a record high of 1,292.37 million
units, valued at 983.87 million Singapore dollars (592.69 million
US dollars). Again, advances overwhelmed declines by 401 to 42,
while 171 other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Renong Bhd continued to be the most actively traded counter as
it registered a turnover of 137.1 million units. It was followed
by Rekapac which had 79.91 million shares traded. Malaya Resources
was next with 54.06 million units changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Local car distributor Cycle &AMP; Carriage (C&AMP;C) led the gainers of
the day as it rose by one dollar to finish at 7.6 Singapore
dollars. DBS (Development Bank of Singapore) Foreign, GE Life, and
GP Battery Warrant0011 increased by 60 cents each to end at 14,
11.4, and 1.88 Singapore dollars respectively. Bukit Sembawang was
up by 55 cents to close at 8.9 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, the Singapore Press Holdings (SPH) was the
biggest loser as it declined by 40 cents to end at 17.7 Singapore
dollars. C. Properties and Creative 50 fell by 20 cents each to
close at 11 and 33.5 Singapore dollars respectively. F&AMP;N and
Jurong Shipyard dropped by 15 cents each to finish at 7.1 and 7.95
Singapore dollars respectively.  
</P>
</TEXT>
