<HEADLINE> Turkey, France to Jointly Produce Antitank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Turkey and France have agreed in
principle to jointly produce a new type of antitank missiles for
the Turkish army, local newspaper Daily News reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted reliable sources from the Turkish General
Staff, whose names were asked not to be mentioned, as saying that
the deal will be worth 450 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Despite objections from some European countries, such as
Germany and Belgium, France is still determined to help Turkey
obtain this new weapon, they added.
</P>
<P>
The antitank missile with a range up to 2,400 meters can be
mounted on military vehicles or used as portable weapons.
</P>
<P>
France, one of the major arms exporters in the world, has been
trying to enter the lucrative Turkish arms market through
breaking the Israeli and U.S. dominance.
</P>
<P>
According to earlier reports, France is also among those
countries competing for Turkey's 4.5 billion-dollar defense
project for main battle tank production.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, which has the second largest standing army among the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization countries, has to import about
79 percent of its military equipment needs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
