<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> El Nino Meeting Calls for Establishing Information </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 6 (Xinhua) -- The Asian regional conference
on El Nino ended here Friday after issuing a statement stressing
the importance of setting up an information system.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the Asian regional meeting on El Nino
related crises calls upon national governments, regional and
international organizations to:
</P>
<P>
-- Establish a regional forum of climate experts (national,
regional, international) to engage in ongoing dialogues to provide
guidance to the countries of the region; and
</P>
<P>
-- Establish a regional strategic planning committee
representative of key stakeholder groups in the region.
</P>
<P>
The statement said all countries concerned should commit to
providing the political and financial support necessary to
establish such a system.
</P>
<P>
The three-day meeting, co-organized by the Asian Disaster
Preparedness Center and the U.S. National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration, brought together more than 100 weather experts to
discuss weather anomalies thought to be caused by El Nino.
</P>
<P>
El Nino is the name given to the occasional warming of surface
waters in the central and eastern equatorial Pacific ocean. It
causes disruption of the ocean-atmosphere system in the tropical
Pacific, with important consequences for the weather around the
globe such as increased rainfall, flooding, drought, bush fires
and hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
"Effects of climate variations can be significantly mitigated
and the positive aspects can be capitalized upon," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
It said there is urgent need to interface between climate
information and user community to address the short term and long
term problems of vulnerability to climate variations.
</P>
<P>
The statement identified the following key action areas towards
building regional capacities:
</P>
<P>
-- Developing a regional capability to produce climate
information guidance;
</P>
<P>
-- Disseminating information on potential impacts on key
sectors such as agriculture and food security, environment and
natural resources, population and public health and industry and
economics;
</P>
<P>
-- Coordinating various regional initiatives;
</P>
<P>
-- Promoting and strengthening the use of existing technical
capacities in the region;
</P>
<P>
-- Strengthening capacities of governments and institutions to
respond; and
</P>
<P>
-- Sharing best practices.
</P>
<P>
The participants formally acknowledged the value of long term
forecasts in alleviating social and economic costs related to
climate variations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
