<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hainan Becoming Major Chinese Industrial Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Industrial output of Hainan,
China's island province, was 17.9 billion yuan (2.2 billion
U.S. dollars) in 1997, a 13 percent increase from the previous
year, according to local statistics.
</P>
<P>
Industrial product sales were 95 percent of the total, up two
percentage points from 1996, and exports grew 30 percent to 150
million U.S. dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Annual growth of investment in industrial fixed assets has been
20 percent since the province was founded 10 years ago, and the
petrochemical, automobile, beverage and food, textile, medicine
and building material industries are playing an important role in
local economic development.
</P>
<P>
The petrochemical industry has become a pillar of economic
development. Work will begin soon on a gas fertilizer project
costing 15.6 billion yuan, and the province is expected to be the
country's largest carbamide production base. The Shilu Iron Mine
Plant, Chahe Cement Plant, Daguangba Power Station, and Yinggehai
Saltern are now operating.
</P>
<P>
Hainan now has more than 50 medicine producers. There were only
five in 1978.
</P>
<P>
The 31-square-kilometer Yangpu Economic Development Zone has
become a large investment project base and the country's largest
export-oriented bonded zone.
</P>
<P>
To increase competitiveness and economic returns, 100
state-owned industrial enterprises, accounting for 40 percent of
the province's total, have been reorganized through various forms
including merger, acquisition, shareholding, or bankruptcy, and
the province has introduced more modern equipment, technology, and
production lines from abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
