<HEADLINE> Pak Asks UN to Be Impartial Mediator on Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Secretary
Shamshad Ahmed has said it was important for the U.N. to quickly
establish its credentials to the Afghan parties as an impartial
mediator, the official APP reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Shamshad made the remarks when he met with a delegation from
the European Union Wednesday, according to the Associated Press of
Pakistan (APP).
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the EU delegation's visit was to convey the
"common European Union position" on Afghanistan, APP said.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani foreign secretary made a detailed briefing to the
EU delegation on the current situation in Afghanistan, it said.
</P>
<P>
Shamshad also explained Pakistan's role in bringing permanent
peace in the neighboring country.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan wants the U.N. to play a central role for an eventual
settlement in Afghanistan, he said, adding that Pakistan is making
hectic efforts to promote the Afghan peace process in support of
the U.N.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, Pakistan is seeking support from the countries,
which have influence in Afghanistan including the six countries
with common borders with Afghanistan (Pakistan, Iran,
Turkmenistan, Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and China) plus the United
States and Russia, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
