<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 09:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diplomat: Iraq Poses No Threat to Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Iraq cherishes its friendship
with Turkey and will never be a threat to this neighboring
country, a senior Iraqi diplomat in Ankara said.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with local newspaper Daily News and
published Friday, Iraqi Charge d'Affaires Saad Al Samarral denied
the claims that Iraq targets its weapons of mass destruction on
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
"The people of Iraq and Turkey are brothers and sisters.
So why should Iraq threaten the Turkish people?" Samarrai said.
</P>
<P>
He added "We enjoy special and historical ties. Our aim is to
further enhance our relations."
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi diplomat pointed out that those allegations that
Iraq's weapons are targeted against Turkey is simply trying to
sow the seeds of discord between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Denying that Iraq has weapons of mass destruction, Samarral
said that the futile action of the numerous U.N. arms inspection
teams was a convincing proof that Iraq does not possess such
weapons.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq's only concern is how its people will be fed and
provided with medicine. It does not have the intention of
launching another war in the region which could not bear another
confrontation," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is ridiculous to describe those people
threatened by powerful Western countries as a nation which poses
a threat to the region.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Britain are amassing their military
force in the Gulf region for a possible strike against Iraq
in order to enforce an unrestricted arms inspection in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
At present, France, Russia, Turkey are making diplomatic
efforts to persuade the Iraqi leadership to comply with the
relevant U.N. Security Council resolution in return for a
peaceful solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has said it favors a diplomatic settlement of the
stand-off between Iraq and the United States, saying that a new
war will harm the region.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, a close ally of the United States, has said that
Washington has not made a request of using the Incirlik air base
in southern Turkey for a military operation against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.S. warplanes stationed in the air base have
obviously increased taking-off and landing flights during the
past days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
