<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Less Burdened by Overbuilt Property Sector: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Throughout Asia, the Philippines
is less burdened by an overbuilt property sector, substantial
excess capacity and mountains of external debts.
</P>
<P>
This was the outcome of a study conducted by Merill Lynch, a
U.S.-based investment management and research company, included in
its Asia Pacific 1998 outlook, the Philippine News Agency reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The study, however, noted that high interest rates have to be
tapped to provide an effective remedy to at least reduce
consumption to more sustainable levels and to fund a looming
fiscal deficit.
</P>
<P>
The peso depreciation and spiked interest rates were also seen
as factors that have contributed to the drop in the growth of
corporate earnings.
</P>
<P>
This resulted in the fall of profits by some listed firms to 10
percent in the third quarter of last year, it said, adding that
this brought the nine-month profit tally to a growth rate of only
9 percent.
</P>
<P>
In spite of the drawbacks of the currency crisis, the property
sector is seen to recover quickly, but the improved performance
will not go beyond five percent this year, it predicted.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the worst still lies ahead for the banks due
to the lag in bad loan recognition," Merill Lynch said.
</P>
<P>
It further noted that the downward pressure on net asset values
for property companies will not be fully realized until later in
1998 or until the banks have fully disposed of the properties held
as collaterals for the bad loans.
</P>
<P>
Merill Lynch said that the lag in non-performing loan
recognition suggests that the bad news for banks might not occur
until later this year.
</P>
<P>
But as high interest rates dominate the property market, unit
sales are likely to weaken as net asset values will not come from
distressed property companies but from banks which wanted to
unload properties used as collaterals, it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
