<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legal System Guarantees Better Conditions for Teachers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Major improvements in China's
education system, including codes and regulations, guarantee
better pay and living conditions for Chinese teachers.
</P>
<P>
The Law on Teachers went into effect on January 1, 1994. More
than half of the country's provinces, municipalities directly
under the Central Government and autonomous regions have since
issued local laws designed to improve overall conditions for
teachers.
</P>
<P>
Laws and regulations adopted by Beijing, Tianjin and Fujian
Province, as well as a number of other municipalities and
provinces, clearly stipulate that wages for teachers must be
higher than those for civil servants.
</P>
<P>
A number of provinces have also introduced regulations
providing teachers with higher than average per-capita housing
space at preferential prices.
</P>
<P>
Six laws, 16 administrative codes and more than 200 regulations
regarding education and teachers have been issued nationwide.
</P>
<P>
In addition, various provinces plan to introduce additional
local codes and regulations during 1998 to provide greater
guarantees covering salaries and living conditions for teachers.
</P>
<P>
China's long tradition of exhibiting great respect for teachers
was virtually destroyed during the 10-year tumultuous "Cultural
Revolution" (1966-1976).
</P>
<P>
However, the growing attention the entire nation has paid to
education and the plight of teachers since the introduction of the
reform and opening polices in the late 1970s can be largely
attributed to persistent calls issued by late Senior Chinese
leader Deng Xiaoping. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong Tailors Enjoy Brisk Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Foreign and domestic tailors
alike are edging into the popular ready-to-wear clothing market in
Guangzhou, capital of south China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
"A tailor-made pair of slacks and long skirt cost around 100
yuan, compared to several hundred yuan for expensive high quality
Western-style clothing. Tailor-made clothing not only equals items
offered in large department stores, but more importantly offers
fine workmanship," according to a young female accountant.
</P>
<P>
A number of foreign-funded shops have joined the competition,
with most offering high quality clothing fashioned according to
individual specifications.
</P>
<P>
Many consumers visit foreign shops for wedding gowns or
evening dresses. Young people, on the other hand, are willing to
pay as much as 3,000 yuan for Western-style clothing such as
suits. Clothing ensembles are popular items with people in higher
income brackets, according to a clerk in a foreign-funded shop.
</P>
<P>
Most small domestic tailors are equipped with a sewing machine,
tape measure and iron. Nonetheless, profitable small shops are
able to compete due to their large clientele of urbanites.
</P>
<P>
Domestic shops also offer traditional clothing styles,
including cheongsam, or tight-fitting dresses with slit skirts and
high necks, as well as Chinese-style jackets with buttons, and
tunic suits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
