<HEADLINE> Cleaner Drinking Water Coming Out of China's Yellow River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Residents of Lanzhou, the
capital of China's Gansu Province, now have cleaner water to drink
from the Yellow River, one of China's biggest rivers, thanks to a
water purification technique developed by Chinese scientists.
</P>
<P>
The part of the river that flows through the city has become
seriously polluted because of the industrial and human waste
discharged into it. The situation had gotten so bad that the
city's drinking water supply was inadequate.
</P>
<P>
To remedy this, the Lanzhou branch of the Chinese Academy of
Sciences developed the water purification equipment specifically
designed to handle the river water's high density of oil-based
pollutants.
</P>
<P>
The equipment can be produced at a low cost and is efficient
and effective at bringing the polluted water up to state-set
standards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Military, Rebels Agree on Repositioning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Negotiators of the Philippine
government and a major Muslim rebel group will sign an agreement
Friday on the repositioning of both forces and some other things,
a top rebel leader said.
</P>
<P>
Ghadzali Jaafar, vice chairman of the Moro Islamic Liberation
Front (MILF), said that negotiators from both sides will sign the
accord at the end of their two-day initial peace talks late Friday
in Marawi City, capital of Lanao de Sur province.
</P>
<P>
Jaafar said that the accord is in line with the provisions
contained in the general agreement for cessation of hostilities in
Mindanao signed in July 1997 by the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Under the accord, all government troops will pull back five
kilometers away from the defense line of MILF's Camp Abubakar in
Buldon town, Maguindanao province. The camp is MILF's largest
stronghold in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The accord also provides for the reactivating of a
government-MILF coordinating committee to monitor any future
ceasefire violations.
</P>
<P>
A joint military-MILF quick response team will be established
to respond on any future conflict between the MILF guerrillas and
the military.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to meet again on February 24-25 in Marawi
city to tackle the agenda of the formal peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The government and the MILF began their exploratory peace talks
in January 1997, but the talks have been on and off due to
sporadic conflicts between the two forces.
</P>
<P>
Boasting a membership of about 12,000, the MILF is presently
the strongest anti-government force in the Philippines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Computer Speaks Chinese Language </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have
developed a Chinese language software system that can give any
text of Chinese language naturally and correctly, "China
Scientific News" reported.
</P>
<P>
This means substantial progress in a key area of China's
intelligent computer research on the Chinese language transfer
system, with a sound data bank for the Chinese language.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Wang Renhua, the project's chief scientist, told
reporters that the computer can say easily distinct and
understable compound sentences and has wide applications for
language terminals, language study, and interpreting.
</P>
<P>
The system's software can also be used to help blind people
read, provide various multimedia sound service using the telephone
network, and translate text files on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, further research is underway to speed up its
application process, according to Prof. Wang.  
</P>
</TEXT>
