<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Low Copper Production Bars Zambia's Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, February 6 (Xinhua) -- The low copper production and
subsequent decline in its prices are the main reasons why
Zambia's economy only grew 3.5 percent instead of the targeted
5.5 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia Friday quoted a quarterly Economic Review
report released by the Barclays Bank (Zambia) as saying
that the lower economic growth rate resulted from the slump in
Zambia's copper production, the country's biggest foreign
exchange earner, and its prices respectively.
</P>
<P>
However, the report said that following the ongoing
privatisation of the copper mines, the economy will improve even
though the fruits should be expected after one to two years.
</P>
<P>
"As the rehabilitation of the mines will take some time, it is
unlikely that the impact of privatisation on exports will be felt
before the fourth quarter of 1998, and then only in relatively
small way," the report said.
</P>
<P>
It said that the process of the rehabilitation in the
privatised mines should be a source of employment because the
owners would demand local skills in engineering and construction
sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Opposition Registers No-confidence Motion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's main opposition party
registered Friday a no-confidence motion against the present
government in the Parliament Secretariat two days after King
Birendra decided to call a special session of parliament.
</P>
<P>
Those signed on the censure motion are 89 MPs from the
Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxism-Leninism, CPN-UML) and
one from the breakaway faction of the ruling National Democratic
Party (RPP) led by Prime Minister Surya Bahadur Thapa, the
Parliament Secretariat said.
</P>
<P>
King Birendra had appointed February 11 for the special
parliament session. But under Nepal's laws, voting on the censure
motion in the Lower House can take place 10 days after the motion
is registered.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that at the February 11 session, the speaker
will set a fresh date for discussions of the motion.
</P>
<P>
A simple majority of 103 votes is needed to pass the censure
motion in the 205-seat Lower House.
</P>
<P>
"We have enough votes to bring down the government," press
reports Friday quoted Man Mohan Adhikari, president of the
CPN-UML, as saying.
</P>
<P>
He did not give details, but said that former prime minister
Lokendra Bahadur Chand, leader of the breakaway faction of RPP,
had assured his party that he has enough votes to pass the
no-confidence motion.
</P>
<P>
The political crisis in the country erupted on January 8 when
Prime Minister Thapa, who came to power last October, recommended
the King to dissolve parliament and hold mid-term elections to
forestall a move by 96 MPs from the CPN-UML and his own party to
plan a censure motion against his coalition government.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, these MPs submitted a petition to King
Birendra demanding a special session of parliament to discuss
their no-confidence motion against the government.
</P>
<P>
Last Wednesday, King Birendra took the Supreme Court's advice
and accepted the submission by the legislators.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
