<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Review Education Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria is to review its
national policy on education promulgated in 1981 and make the
French language compulsory in all secondary schools in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Far reaching decisions are expected to be discussed at the
National Council on Education meeting later this month, the
Guardian reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian head of state General Sani Abacha has been personally
advocating French as the second official language of the country,
which is surrounded by French-speaking countries and suffering
setbacks in its relations with English-speaking western
countries.
</P>
<P>
The program is also expected to boost economic and trade
relations with French-speaking countries in the west African
sub-region.
</P>
<P>
As the first step to popularize French, Nigeria set up a
French language center in Lagos later last year and the
government is planning another in Nassarawa State in the central
part of the country near the national capital of Abuja.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted a source close to the presidency
as disclosing that a decree on the adoption of French as an
officially recognized language in Nigeria is now before the head
of state.
</P>
<P>
A task force on the development of French headed by an eminent
linguist is underway to ensure effective implementation of the
policy on the language.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that about 15,000 teachers would be required
for the program in secondary schools, with each school having two
teachers.
</P>
<P>
France has expressed its willingness to assist in the program,
suggesting that Nigeria facilitate French teaching by massive
recruitment of qualified teachers from neighboring
French-speaking countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
