<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Probing Report on Egypt Trade Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Israel is probing the report
that Egypt has banned the import of a variety of Israeli goods,
local English daily The Jerusalem Post reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Foreign Ministry's legal adviser Alan
Baker has recommended a meeting of the joint Israeli-Egyptian
trade committee to examine a report on the Egyptian daily Al
Ahram that Egypt is banning import of Israeli medicines,
cosmetics and other items.
</P>
<P>
A report published on Al Ahram late last month quoted Egypt's
Deputy Health Minister Jamila Moussa as saying that stringent
instructions have been given to customs stations to ban the entry
of Israeli medicines, cosmetics and some other goods.
</P>
<P>
Baker said that if the report is true, Egypt would be in
violation of both the 1979 peace treaty and the 1980 trade
agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry is analyzing a document from Baker
listing three agreements which may have been breached. According
to the agreements, the countries should allow free movement of
goods, vehicles and nationals, and both sides should inform the
other of any change in trade relationship.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Ambassador to Israel Mohammed Bassiouny confirmed the
report on the Al Ahram, but he noted that the Egyptian measures
are similar to those already imposed by Israel banning the import
of Egyptian textiles or water pipes. He stressed that Egyptian
government's strategy is not to place obstacles or prevent trade
with Israel, but rather let the market to regulate it.
</P>
<P>
One Israeli Foreign Ministry official was quoted by the
Jerusalem Post as saying that while this issue is serious, Israel
will keep a low-key profile in dealing with the matter because
Israel does not want to hurt the already strained bilateral ties
caused by the deadlock in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade between Israel and Egypt totaled 85 million
U.S. dollars last year, compared to 60 million dollars in
1996. Israeli pharmaceutical export to Egypt last year rose
slightly from 11,100 dollars in 1996 to 11,500 dollars, and
Egypt's textiles export to Israel increased from 1.7 million
dollars to 3.1 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
