<HEADLINE> U.S. Delegation Hopes to Best Its Lillehammer Medals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 6 (Xinhua) -- The delegation of the United
States, which sends 196-strong athletes for the Nagano Winter Olympics
opening Saturday, hopes to expected the country's best yet the
Lillehammer Games performance in 1994.
</P>
<P>
"In 1994 we won 13 medals and more importantly achieved a high
number of personal bests," said Bill Hybl, president of the United
States Olympic committee on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We think this time the US will do as well or even better than in
the past," Hybl continuted. But he didn't said how many medals they
want to gain this time.
</P>
<P>
The United States won six golds, five silvers and two bronzes in
Lilleammer, ranked fifth in the gold medal standings. Russia won the
most golds with 11, followed by host Norway with 10, Germany nine and
Italy seven.
</P>
<P>
The delegation chief Paul George Said there had been few problems
and few controversies among the athletes who are "very, very excited."
</P>
<P>
"To exceed Lillehammer would be a great thrill and it would show we
are directionally headed to Salt Lake City in 2002 with a strong
competitive team," George added.
</P>
<P>
The 196 athletes are the most figures in the Nagano Winter
Olympics, followed by host Japan with 166 and Switzerland with 163.
</P>
