<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB to Grant One Billion Dollars to Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 6 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has agreed to
provide one billion U.S. dollars in loans this year to help the
Philippines deal with the effects of the current financial crisis,
WB President James Wolfensohn said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn, who is on a five-nation tour in Asia, said that the
loans would be on top of the 350 million dollars the World Bank
programmed for the country annually.
</P>
<P>
"I indicated to them that in addition to the 350 million
dollars that we typically advance each year, we are looking at a
special program of one billion dollars to cover structural
reforms, social sector and infrastructure that may be provided
urgently as you need it," he said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Wolfensohn praised the Philippines for weathering
the financial crisis better than its neighbors hit by the
financial turmoil, although he said that there was still a need to
tighten supervision of the banking system.
</P>
<P>
"What is very clear is that the Philippine situation is largely
different from South Korea, Thailand and Indonesia," he said.
</P>
<P>
"While there are also some disturbances, while quite obviously
the foreign exchange market has weakened, the stock market has
weakened, I think you all know that you (the Philippines) have
weakened less than the region with the exception of Singapore," he
said.
</P>
<P>
During his 24-hour visit to the Philippines, Wolfensohn met
with President Fidel Ramos, economic managers, business executives
and trade union leaders.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn commended Ramos for doing a remarkable job by
putting in social, economic and political reforms, thereby making
the Philippines the "least affected country" in the currency
storm.
</P>
<P>
Ramos briefed Wolfensohn on the economic situation in the
country and the remaining measures the government is taking,
including strict implementation of sound fiscal management and
discipline, to contain the effects of the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn is leaving for South Korea Friday. He has also
visited Thailand, Singapore, Malaysia and Indonesia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
