<P>
WASHINGTON -- President Bill Clinton has decided to send about
2,200 U.S. Marines on board warship from the Mediterranean to the
Gulf to join the already might military force in the region,
U.S. defense officials said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The move came as time was ticking close to a possible military
showdown with Iraq over its refusal to allow weapons inspectors'
access to presidential sites.
</P>
<P>
The 24th marine Expeditionary Unit aboard the helicopter
carrier Guam and three support ships would join a force of some 20
other U.S. warships already there, including the aircraft carriers
Nimitz, George Washington. And the third aircraft carrier
Independent also entered the Gulf region on Thursday with 75
aircraft aboard and a battle group that includes a cruiser, a
destroyer and a submarine. (US-Iraq-Showdown)
</P>
