<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Support Opening-Up  Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 6 (Xinhua) -- A recent opinion poll revealed
that Chinese citizens are fully satisfied with the remarkable
successes achieved since the country adopted reform and opening-up
policies nearly two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
The poll was taken by the Beijing Horizon Market Survey &AMP;
Analysis Company.
</P>
<P>
The survey of over 5,000 permanent residents in ten large
cities, including Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou, Chengdu and
Shenyang, indicated that 34.6 percent of respondents felt that
China has reached an appropriate opening-up level, with 24.9
percent indicating that the country should open wider to the
outside world.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-one percent noted the imbalance in opening-up levels for
different regions throughout the nation, and 11 percent indicated
that the pace of opening-up should be slowed somewhat.
</P>
<P>
When compared to a similar survey in 1995, the number of
respondents satisfied with the current status of the opening-up
effort jumped by 14 percent, with the number citing regional
imbalances falling by 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
The survey suggests that the fall in the latter figure resulted
from China's increased emphasis on reform and opening-up in inland
and western areas, and improving management policies governing
foreign capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
