<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Waste Water Treatment Plant in Operation in Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Construction of the Zhengzhou
Waste Water Treatment Plant, the biggest in the Huaihe River
valleys, has begun in Zhengzhou, capital of central China's Henan
Province, the People's Daily has reported.
</P>
<P>
The 761 million yuan (92 million US dollars) project, which is
being built with loans from Japan and the State Development Bank,
will be able to treat 400,000 tons of waste water a day when its
first phase is completed.
</P>
<P>
The Huaihe River runs through Henan, Anhui, Jiangsu and Shandong
provinces, the country's major grain and energy producers.
Located on the upper reaches of the river, Zhengzhou
discharges nearly a million tons of waste water into the river
each day.
</P>
<P>
The water quality of the river, one of China's longest,
is showing signs of improving thanks to a massive pollution
control campaign last year.
</P>
<P>
On January 1 this year, the anti-pollution battle entered its
second phase.
</P>
<P>
The country has planned to build 47 urban waste water treatment
plants in the valleys by the year 2000. The plants are expected to
cut the release of pollutants by 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that China will spend nearly 20 billion yuan
on pollution control projects in the Huaihe River valleys during
the 1998-2000 period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Brazilian Climbers Die on Aconcagua </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, February 5 (Xinhua) -- Three Brazilian climbers
scaling the Aconcagua Mountain, the tallest in the Americas, have
died in avalanches, Argentine authorities said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The trio, identified as Othon Leonardos, Alexandre Da Silva
D'Oliveira and Mozart Hastenreidr Camaud, were among the five
Brazilians who had encountered blizzards at 6,000 metres. The
other two survived to retreat to a safer lower attitude.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilians had tried to climb the dangerous southern face
of the 7,000-meter-high mountain on the border of central
Argentina and Chile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
