<HEADLINE> Soaked Volumes of Stanford University to be Freeze-dried </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, February 5 (Xinhua) -- More than 60,000 soaked
books from a library at Stanford University have been moved to a
local cold storage company to be freeze-dried.
</P>
<P>
Two days' drenching rains caused by El Nino earlier this week
hit California hard, flooding the whole campus and the library's
basement where 120,000 books were shelved.
</P>
<P>
The whole drying process will take three months and the vast
majority of the volumes could be restored and returned to library
shelves, according to engineers.
</P>
<P>
Twenty years ago, another Stanford library was flooded and
44,000 books were damaged. Most of the books later got preserved
with the help of Lockheed Missile and Space Co. which offered a
vacuum chamber for use in the drying process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
