<HEADLINE> Liaoning Scores Technological Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Liaoning, a traditional heavy
industrial base in northeast China, invested 24 billion yuan in
technological transformations during 1997, up 20 percent on the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of investment went to 250 key projects at 26
provincial technical centers and 100 experimental high-tech
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,300 local industrial firms had used foreign funding to
upgrade their technology by the end of last November.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government plans to allocate 24.5 billion yuan
to upgrade the technology of the ten key projects in six pillar
industrial sectors during 1998, including the computer and
software, new materials, modern telecommunications,
bio-pharmaceutical sector, electric machinery, and fine chemical
industry, and their 1998 output value is expected to reach 50
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The sector will attract 1.5 billion yuan from abroad to
facilitate the technological cooperation between medium- to
large-sized local state-owned firms and the world's top 500
companies.
</P>
<P>
A mere 10 percent of equipment in Liaoning's state-owned
enterprises was installed during the 1980s, with obsolete
equipment dating to the 1950s, accounting for 30 percent of the
remainder.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
