<HEADLINE> Official Calls for Early Political Talks Across Taiwan Straits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 6 (Xinhua) -- An official in charge of
relations across the Taiwan Straits has said that high-level political
talks between the mainland and Taiwan are so crucial that they
cannot be sidestepped.
</P>
<P>
Tang Shubei, vice-chairman of the mainland-based Association
for Relations Across the Taiwan Straits (ARATS), was quoted in a
recent interview with Beijing's monthly "Cross-Straits Relations"
as saying the political talks are unavoidable for cross-strait
relations this year.
</P>
<P>
He said that President Jiang Zemin and Vice-Premier Qian Qichen
have repeatedly called for talks to end the hostilities, under the
one-China principle.
</P>
<P>
There has been no explicit response from Taiwan authorities so
far, he said, but the significance of these talks is recognized by
a growing number of Taiwanese, and it is high time that the two
sides held procedural talks.
</P>
<P>
If ARATS and SEF (the Taiwan-based Straits Exchange Foundation)
can meet, he said, they could make proper arrangements to talk
about the agenda, the capacity of representatives, and in what way
the talks should be held. But, these negotiations depend on the
sincerity of the Taiwan authorities.
</P>
<P>
Tang expressed the hope that contacts between ARATS and SEF can
be increased this year and that there can be visits of senior
officials. He said that ARATS will continue to promote exchanges
and visits, including those of mayors and county heads. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
