<HEADLINE> Bad Weather Still Problem for Nagano Ski Course </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Nagano Winter Olympics ski
officials still face a possible bad Weather problem which may force
the starting point for the downhill race to be lowered, ski officals
said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We have drawn up 40 alternative schedules for the competitions in
case races are postponed due to bad weather," said one official, at
Happo-one slopes in Hakuba, site of the Olympics Nordic and Alpine ski
events.
</P>
<P>
The Official said heavy snow was forecast for the area for the
opening day of the Alpine ski competition on Sunday. "We consider it's
lucky if we have fine four days out of all days set aside for the
competitions," he added.
</P>
<P>
The downhill race on the 3.28-kilometer course could be postponded
if snow conditions or fog threaten the safety of athletes. And if the
race postponed, other events that follow will be rescheduled, the ski
officials said.
</P>
<P>
They also said they would like to hold the race starting from the
higher point, but have to wait until the last moment to decide whether
to use the lower start. 
</P>
</TEXT>
