<HEADLINE> Foreigners in Beijing Pay Individual Income Tax in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Foreigners in Beijing paid 1.22
billion yuan (145 million US dollars) in individual income tax in
1997, according to the Municipal Taxation Bureau.
</P>
<P>
This came from foreigners working in Beijing and Chinese
employees in Beijing-based foreign enterprises, according to a
government official.
</P>
<P>
The official said 8,000 foreigners and 220,000 Chinese paid
individual income tax last year, but the latter accounted
for 28 percent of the total amount.
</P>
<P>
The taxpayers were mainly from the United States, Japan,
Germany and Hong Kong, the official said, and more than half
of foreign taxpayers were taxed at rates above 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the Municipal Taxation Bureau, foreigner-related
taxes were up 21 percent to reach 3.6 billion yuan in 1997,
because of Beijing's rapid economic development and improving
investment environment.
</P>
<P>
</P>
