<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Launch Leprosy Elimination Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, February 6 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government will
launch a six-day national lerposy elimination campaign in October
this year to detect about 40,000 leprosy patients in the country
and bring them under the treatment program, the independent United
News Bangaldesh (UNB) reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The campaign will create a national awareness on leprosy, with
the aim of achieving the goal of eliminating leprosy by the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
With an estimated 40,000 undetected cases, Bangaldesh has
remained one of the six most endemic countries of lerposy in the
world.
</P>
<P>
A total of 43,313 new cases were registered for treatment
between January 1993 and September 1997 while 41,698 patients have
been cured in the past five years. Over 23,000 registered patients
have developed deformities during this period.
</P>
<P>
The government, with the help of the World Health Organization
(WHO) and other development partners, has sufficient drugs for
treating all the leprosy patients free of charge, and drugs are
now available in Bangaldesh at 600 treatment centers. And a total
of 31,117 doctors, medical and nursing students and general health
staff have been given training and direction on leprosy.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, adequate facilities for treating leprosy patients is
available in 11 hospitals in Bangladesh which have a total of 464
beds.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0233 </DOCNO>
