<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Toll Rises to 46 From Philippine Air Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-five mangled bodies were
retrieved Friday morning in the crash site of a DC-9 plane on a
southern Philippine ridge, bringing the death toll to 46, rescuers
said.
</P>
<P>
"We are expecting more bodies since a bigger portion of the
aircraft's fuselage crashed in our area," Gerald Navarro, a leader
of a local mountaineering club, reported Friday morning from Mt.
Lumot in Claveria Town, Misamis Oriental Province.
</P>
<P>
Rescuers from the club Thursday morning reached Mt. Lumot, a
nearby ridge of Mt. Sumagaya where the Cebu Pacific Airways' DC-9
plane crashed and exploded Monday.
</P>
<P>
"A bigger portion of the aircraft remains intact but it is
covered by soil due to landslide when the aircraft hit the
ground," Navarro added.
</P>
<P>
The twin-engine plane carrying 104 people was on its way to
Cagayan de Oro City from Manila Monday morning when it crashed 15
minutes before it was supposed to land. All aboard were feared
dead.
</P>
<P>
"We have now accounted for 40 bodies, including the 11 bodies
accounted Thursday afternoon, and the number may rise if the
aircraft is cleared of soil," Navarro said.
</P>
<P>
According to Navarro, the bodies strewn over Mt. Lumot were
badly mutilated, some of them naked, but could be identified by
experts.
</P>
<P>
Six other bodies were separately accounted for by ground rescue
groups in Mt. Sumagaya headed by Col. Jacinto Ligot Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
The bodies will be transported to Cagayan de Oro City for
forensic examination.
</P>
<P>
The weather condition in the vicinity of the crash site was
favorable but air rescuers still failed to drop supplies to
Navarro's men due to the dense forest.
</P>
<P>
Navarro said helicopters could not land until a landing pad was
made in the area. "But, we need chainsaws to clear the forest
since trees in the crash site are big."
</P>
<P>
He said their group needed deodorizer powder, gloves, shovel
and cadaver bags.  
</P>
</TEXT>
