<HEADLINE> Indian PM Writes to Annan for Peace in Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Following up his January 30
letter to U.S. President Bill Clinton and the heads of the other
four permanent members of the United Nations Security Council on
the escalating Iraqi crisis, Indian Prime Minister Inder Kumar
Gujral Thursday wrote a letter to U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan for the same purpose, official sources said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
In his letter, Gujral reiterated India's support for the U.N.
resolutions relating to Iraq while stating that the use of
military force against Iraq would only serve to complicate the
situation.
</P>
<P>
Any military conflict would aggravate the enormous suffering
that the Iraqis had undergone under the sanctions regime, he
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Gujral expressed his concern particularly for the plight of
women and children who were the most adversely affected section of
the people and were the main victims of malnutrition and shortage
of medical supplies.
</P>
<P>
He also praised the U.N. secretary general's plea to accord
primacy to the process of diplomatic negotiations and his offer of
mediation and reiterated India's readiness to contribute to the
process of bringing about a peaceful solution through diplomatic
parleys.  
</P>
