<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan Labor Minister John
Seneviratne has called for the plantation management companies and
trade unions to hold another round of talks Friday in a bid to end
a nation-wide strike which began on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ceylon Planters Association Chairman Mahendra Amarasuriya said
representatives of the association would attend the meeting
convened by the minister to settle the dispute over a wage hike.
</P>
<P>
About 600,000 workers in tea and rubber estates began the
strike Thursday after talks with their employers broke down.
</P>
<P>
The unions demanded a wage hike from the present daily salary
of 83 Rupees (1.34 U.S. dollars) to 105 Rupees (1.69 dollars)
while their companies only agreed to pay 93 Rupees (1.5 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Seneviratne had intervened on Tuesday, urging the companies to
offer 100 Rupees (1.61 dollars) as a compromise.
</P>
<P>
Industry experts have warned that a minimum seven Rupees
increase on the basic wage would cost the industry at least 1
billion Rupees (16.1 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The last strike by estate workers was in April 1996. It lasted
one week and cost an estimated 500 million Rupees (8.1 million
dollars).  
</P>
