<HEADLINE> Samaranch Supports Both Clinton and Olympic Truce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 6 (Xinhua) -- International Olympic
Committee president Juan Antonio Samaranch trod a political tightrope
on Friday when he said at a press conference that he supported both
U.S. president Clinton and U.N. resolution against military action
during the games.
</P>
<P>
"Our hope -- and I repeat I can only say hope -- is that the
Olympic Truce will be observed."
</P>
<P>
The Olympic chief believed that president Clinton could find a
proper way to solve the problem. "I'm sure he'll find diplomatic
efforts to convince Iraq to respect the U.N.," he said, adding his
voice to the mounting IOC and U.N. effort to have some impact on
American policy in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Washington said the United States has warned that it
may take military action against Iraq unless it allows U.N. inspectors
unrestricted access in carrying out the weapons inspection.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Samaranch also emphasized in the press conference he was
not opposed to the American stance.
</P>
<P>
"I am not against the position of the President Clinton. Clinton
said many times he prefers a diplomatic solution. This is our
position, too," he added.
</P>
<P>
When being asked whether he would travel to the United States or
Iraq as he did to Sarajevo at the Lillehammer Olympic Winter Games
four years ago, the president said:"the power of the Olympic Truce is
limit. We have done what we could possibly do." 
</P>
