<HEADLINE> Mahathir Proposes Regional Trade Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad has proposed a regional trade plan for using
local currencies instead of the U.S. dollar to make purchases in
efforts to ease the currency turbulence hitting Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir made the proposal during his talks with Thai Prime
Minister Chuan Leekpai here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The proposal would encourage buyers from a member country of
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) to use their
own currency to make purchases, and the central banks in the
region would help clear the transactions within three months.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers Friday quoted some Thai officials as saying
that Mahathir's proposal would be feasible among Malaysia, the
Philippines and Thailand because their economies are of compatible
sizes.
</P>
<P>
Trading in local currencies would save ASEAN economies the fees
of buying U.S. dollars, the officials noted.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir arrived here on Thursday and leaves on Friday to
continue his regional tour which will also take him to the
Philippines and Singapore. 
</P>
