<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soft-Money Gifts to Parties Last Year Total 67 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 5 (Xinhua) -- Democratic and Republican
national party organizations in the United States together raised
67 million dollars in unregulated "soft money" last year from
corporations, unions and rich patrons, an advocacy group said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The figure is a record for soft money raised in an off-election
year and more than double the amount raised in 1993, the last
post-presidential-election year, said Common Cause, which wants
such contributions outlawed.
</P>
<P>
Soft money donations are supposed to be used only for
party-building activities like voter registration, but Federal
Election Commission lawyers said last week the parties are finding
ways to circumvent campaign finance laws and use the money to help
federal candidates.
</P>
<P>
In the 1996 election, the two parties raised 262 million
dollars in soft money, most of it from special interests.
</P>
<P>
The Senate is scheduled to vote next month on a bipartisan bill
that would eliminate such contributions.
</P>
<P>
Soft money is one of the fastest-growing and most controversial
types of fund-raising employed by the political parties. Critics
view the donations as a way for special interests to influence
politics; supporters see them as free speech.
</P>
<P>
"Banning soft money is a critically important first step to
address the worst abuses in the political system today... and to
help clean up the presidential system for the year 2000," said Ann
McBride, president of Common Cause.
</P>
<P>
The groups said in its analysis of FEC records that Republicans
raised 40 million dollars and Democrats took in 27 million dollars
in soft money last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 19 Killed in Storms in Eastern U.S. Coast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The storm dumped more than 18 centimeters of rain on Virginia
Beach, Virginia, and swept the South Jersey shoreline on Thursday
with tides 3.3 meters above normal.
</P>
<P>
A storm landed from the south coast and stomped its way north,
flooding streets, stranding travelers, forcing people to evacuate
their homes and leaving tens of thousands of people without
electricity across West Virginia, eastern Kentucky and Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
It brought tornadoes to southern Florida on Monday before
churning to the north, hammering the coast from Georgia to New
Jersey with heavy rain and winds as high as 120 kph.
</P>
<P>
About 50,000 customers along Tennessee's Cumberland Plateau
were without power Thursday. Thousands more lacked electricity in
Virginia, New Jersey, West Virginia, Delaware and Maryland.
</P>
<P>
The storm also has brought snow that blanketed an area from
Ohio to North Carolina. In areas in Kentucky and Ohio, snowfalls
reached more than a 30 centimeters and in the hills of western
Maryland, 50 centimeters of snow were recorded.
</P>
<P>
19 deaths have been attributed to the East Coast storm. Five
were killed in accidents on snowy roads in Kentucky, and two in
Indiana.
</P>
<P>
Two men died when the roof caved in under 11 inches of snow at
a recycling plant in Princeton, West Virginia, and a pregnant
woman drowned when her car plunged into a swollen creek in South
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
A 20-car freight train heading to Roanoke, Virginia, derailed
Thursday morning after floodwaters from the Maury River swept away
an 25-meter section of track.
</P>
<P>
At least 20 house fires were reported in southeastern Virginia
caused by flood waters that spread into homes and soaked oil
heaters, sparking the blazes.
</P>
<P>
Floodwaters up to 1.3 meters deep along New Jersey's coast
forced authorities to close nearly all the access routes to
Atlantic City, Ocean City, Wildwood and other beach towns early
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In the west, severe storm lashed California in the last few
days, leading to street flood in several counties. Governor Pete
Wilson has declared emergencies in 10 counties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
