<HEADLINE> Soeharto Meets Brunei Sultan, Malaysian Deputy PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
held separate talks with Sultan of Brunei Hassanal Bolkianh and
Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim here Thursday, the
local press reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Officials refused to give details of either meeting and said
only that the three leaders focused on the currency crisis
blighting the region.
</P>
<P>
Minister/State Secretary Moerdiono said Soeharto briefed the
Sultan on the current economic crisis in Indonesia and the steps
the country is taking to overcome it.
</P>
<P>
The Sultan and his entourage arrived here Thursday morning. He
was greeted personally by Soeharto at the latter's residence. He
left the country in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Brunei pledged 1.2 billion U.S. dollars in a bilateral loan to
Indonesia in November last year in a bid to shore up the latter's
flagging economy. Malaysia pledged 1 billion dollars despite its
own economic problems.
</P>
<P>
"The purpose of Anwar's visit was to inform the President of
Mahathir's tour of the region," a reliable source, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Mahathir Mohammed and Soeharto met here last
month. Mahathir proposed that Southeast Asian countries use their
own currencies instead of U.S. dollars in their bilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Mahathir Thursday began a tour of Thailand, the
Philippines and Singapore to discuss the regional economic crisis
with fellow members of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN). 
</P>
