<HEADLINE> Water Storage Facilities Help Chinese Province Battle Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Water storage facilities
enabled farmers in central Gansu Province, which was hit by severe
drought in 1997, to enjoy sufficient grain and potable
water during this year's Spring Festival holidays.
</P>
<P>
"The five cisterns near my house will provide enough water for
us until May," said Yang Gong, a farmer in Lujiagou Township
in Dingxi County.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the water storage facilities in Lujiagou, an area
which recorded a mere 80 millimeters of rain in 1997, residents
had no longer to buy water from cities during the Spring
Festival holdays.
</P>
<P>
Yang's five cisterns are full due to ample rainfall in
August. Three cisterns are used to irrigate fruit trees and maize
and the two others provide ample water for the family and its
livestock.
</P>
<P>
Some 90 percent of the families in his village relied on water
storage facilities to raise their livestock. The facilities
enabled them to earn a steady income despite the drought.
</P>
<P>
Gansu, a drought-prone area in northwest China, has encouraged
the construction of water storage facilities as part of the
government poverty relief program.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that Gansu farmers constructed over 440,000
water storage facilities in 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
