<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 40 Bodies Found at Philippine Plane Crash Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 6 (Xinhua) -- At least 40 bodies had been
accounted for by rescuers as of early Friday morning at the crash
site of a DC-9 plane on a southern Philippine mountain, according
to local television reports.
</P>
<P>
Jesus Dureza, a rescue operation leader, told the SNN
television that more body parts believed to be from 29 victims had
been recovered by rescue teams early in the morning, bringing to
40 the number of bodies found.
</P>
<P>
He said the bodies will be moved by foot to the foot of Mt.
Sumagaya and be airlifted to nearby Cagayan de Oro City for
examination and identification.
</P>
<P>
Dureza said more body bags will be delivered to the crash site
as rescuers reported a shortage of bags because of too many
mangled bodies.
</P>
<P>
The exact number of casualties is still unknown as rescuers
continued to scour a one-kilometer-square slope where the Cebu
Pacific DC-9 jetliner crashed Monday and its wreckage and the
victims' bodies were strewn, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Hampered by rains, thick vegetation and snakes, by Friday
morning, rescuers had not yet reached the impact point of the
plane where part of its wreckage, including one of the two
engines, was first sighted by air rescuers Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Rescue officials said earlier there was little hope for any of
the 104 people aboard the ill-starred passenger plane to survive
five days after the crash, the worst ever in the Philippines'
aviation history.
</P>
<P>
The 99 passengers on board the plane included one Japanese, an
Austrian, a Swiss, at least two Americans, an Australian and at
least one Canadian.
</P>
<P>
The twin-engine aircraft slammed into Mt. Sumagaya Monday
morning while approaching the nearby airport of Cagayan de Oro
City, some 800 km south of its departure place Manila.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
