<HEADLINE> Russia Rejects U.S. Human Rights Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 5 (Xinhua) -- A Russian official has denounced
allegations made in a U.S. State Department report on human rights.
</P>
<P>
Gennady Tarasov, director of the foreign ministry's press
bureau, said in a conference Thursday that the U.S. report failed
to take into consideration Russia's democratic progress.
</P>
<P>
The report, Tarasov said, which is similar to previous ones, is
full of flaws. He said the report evaluates the Russian human
rights situation according to American laws and practices.
</P>
<P>
Tarasov said the report not only shows disrespect for the
status of Russian laws, but also neglects the human rights
practices of other nations.
</P>
<P>
Russia, of course, takes into consideration the American
experience. Russia however does not think the American attitude
toward human rights is the only correct one.
</P>
<P>
In response to the criticism of Russia's religious belief law,
he said the law does not exclude non-traditional religions in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The restrictive provisions in the law are directed only toward
extreme doomsday religions, which threaten or violate human life,
family values and the morality of children, said Tarasov. 
</P>
</TEXT>
