<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, February 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
economic news briefs in Latin American countries from the past few
days.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Venezuela registered an inflation two percent lower
in January than that of the same month of 1997, said the Central
Bank.
</P>
<P>
The annual inflation rate until January was 36.8 percent,
compared with 37.6 percent for the same period of the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
The consumer price index showed a downtrend, said Central Bank
authorities.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguay achieved a 272 million U.S. dollar
surplus in its payments in the first nine months in 1997, said the
Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
The surplus helped to improve the capital and financial
accounts, which surged to 361 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The current account closed with an 86 million dollar deficit
because of an increase of imports above exports.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The predicted seven percent unemployment rate in
1998 will affect the economically active population in Brazil,
said the Economic Policy Secretariat of the Brazilian Finance
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The secretariat said the total of Brazilian unemployed could
reach 5.1 million people in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The average unemployment rate was 5.66 percent in 1997 in the
biggest metropolitan areas of the country, according to data
published by the Brazilian Institute of Geography and Statistics.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentine oil exports income will be reduced by
400 million U.S. dollars this year because of the drop of crude
oil prices on the international market
</P>
<P>
According to the Fuels Secretariat, the drop in income amounts
to two percent of total exports and to 13 percent of Argentine oil
exports.
</P>
<P>
Argentine oil income reached 2.5 billion dollars last year, 500
million dollars less than the predicted three billion dollars
before the prices collapse.
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Brazilian paper output last year was 6.5
million tons, a 4.2 percent increase over that of 1996.
</P>
<P>
About 21.5 percent of that total, was exported and the
remainder went on domestic consumption, said the Brazilian
Cellulose and Paper Association (Bracelpa) in a report published
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Paper exports income in 1997 reached 980 million U.S. dollars,
a 4.8 percent increase over the previous year. Internal
consumption increased 3.5 percent last year, compared with 1996.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chilean poultry exports amounted to 35.1 million
U.S. dollars in 1997, a 25.6 percent increase compared to the
previous year, said the Chilean Poultry Producers Association.
</P>
<P>
Most of the exports went to American countries and Europe, with
44.1 percent and 41.1 percent of the total, respectively, while
exports to Asia were 13.1 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
