<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Congress to Pass New Oil Deregulation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 6 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' bicameral
Congress will ratify Friday a compromise version of the new oil
deregulation bill which is vital for the country's exit from the
supervision of the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
A bicameral committee, composed of representatives from both
the Lower House and the Senate, reached agreement Thursday night
on the proposed oil deregulation bill after more than one month of
bargaining.
</P>
<P>
The old oil deregulation law, which took effect in February
1997, was nullified by the Supreme Court last November on the
grounds that it violated the constitution and the rule of free
trade.
</P>
<P>
The law provided for a 7 percent tariff for refined petroleum
products, and a 3 percent tariff for crude oil, to encourage firms
to invest in the domestic refinery industry.
</P>
<P>
But the Supreme Court ruled that free trade would be hindered
if oil firms were forced to choose between investing huge amounts
in refineries and paying higher tariffs.
</P>
<P>
The abolishment of the old oil deregulation law prevented the
country from getting free from decades of economic supervision by
the IMF before the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Under the compromise oil bill, a uniform 3 percent tariff will
be imposed on both finished oil products and crude oil. The
proposal for a uniform tariff for all oil products was actually
approved by President Fidel Ramos late last year.
</P>
<P>
The bill also provides a 2.9 billion pesos (71 million U.S.
dollars) buffer fund to subsidize oil companies during a
five-month transition period prior to the full deregulation of the
country's oil industry.
</P>
<P>
During the period, oil companies are barred from jacking up
prices of "socially sensitive" products like kerosene and diesel.
But the transition period is "flexible" and Ramos is empowered to
reduce its length for those oil products that are not socially
sensitive.
</P>
<P>
Because of the delayed passage of the new oil deregulation
bill, many new entrants in the local oil industry are considering
closing their operations and put on hold their new investments in
the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Province Begins to Reduce Number of Spindles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, February 6 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu Province
has begun to reduce the number of spindles, as a reform measure to
reshape its textile industry.
</P>
<P>
Provincial government sources said that Jiangsu will take two
years to meet the State-set quota of reducing the spindle number
by 1.01 million. This means that 60,869 textile workers will be
laid off.
</P>
<P>
This year is crucial for the industrial reforms, according to
Governor Zheng Silin.
</P>
<P>
He said that 840,700 spindles will be cut this year and 176,000
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
A work team, made of government officials, is supervising the
reforms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Flotation to Help Chinese Tourist City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Guilin, one of the most popular
and oldest tourist spots in China, plans to issue shares in
China's interior area and in Hongkong to try to save its
money-starved travel industry.
</P>
<P>
Huang Jiacheng, director of the Guilin Tourism Bureau, told
Xinhua that Guilin Tourism Co. Ltd. (GTC) hopes to raise over 1.7
billion yuan (204.8 million US dollars) in this way. It has 700
million yuan in assets and counts major local hotels, scenic
spots, and other tourism enterprises as its main shareholders.
</P>
<P>
The move is designed to help raise funds for an international
convention and exhibition center, a sports center, a holiday
resort, and for the renovation of old hotels and to open new
tourist routes, all of which are badly needed or even crucial to
maintaining its charm, Huang said.
</P>
<P>
Guilin is in the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region. It's known
for its Lijiang River and the surrounding mountains. In 1996, it
had 408,800 overseas tourists who brought in 118.4 million US
dollars, and 10 million domestic tourists. But, its tourism, which
grew by leaps and bounds, has suffered from a shortage of funds in
recent years. This has aroused concern in the central government,
according to Gao Shunli, an official with the China National
Tourism Administration's Department of Policy and Law.
</P>
<P>
"Guilin's importance can never be overestimated because it is
one of the five major attractions with Beijing, Xi'an, Shanghai,
and Guangzhou and its ranking in the country's tourism industry is
quite impressive, when one considers that it is not a provincial
capital," Gao said
</P>
<P>
"We've got everything ready for the listing and are only
waiting for central government approval," Huang explained.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government is supporting the listing, and
Vice-Premier Zhu Rongji personally wrote instructions on documents
related to the matter, he said.
</P>
<P>
When tourism in Guilin develops, it is expected to bring more
tourists to other parts of south China, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
