<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Protecting Ancient Cultural Relics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, February 6 (Xinhua) -- China plans to set up a
protection zone for relics of the Liangzhu Culture, which dates
back more than 4,000 years, in Yuhuang County in Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
State Bureau of Cultural Relics scholars have developed a plan
for research, relics protection, tree-planting, tourism programs,
electricity, communication, and parks at the site.
</P>
<P>
There are 54 historical sites that have been excavated or
ascertained at Liangzhu, according to a State Cultural Relics
Bureau official.
</P>
<P>
One of them is the grand tomb at Fanshan and the altar ruins at
Yaoshan, which were excavated in 1986 and 1987.
</P>
<P>
Near the town of Liangzhu, archaeologists discovered the
Mojiaoshan Ruins, a 310,000-sq.m. area of building remains, in
1993.
</P>
<P>
These relics are important for the study of the 5,000-year-old
Chinese civilization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
