<DOCNO> XIE19980206.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Bodies Found at Philippine Plane Crash Site, No </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Rescue operations in the
Philippine air crash entered the fifth day Friday after 11 bodies
and many body parts had been found at the crash site of a DC-9
plane on a southern jungle-covered mountain as of Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
Local television reports quoted rescue officials as saying
there is little hope for any of the 104 people aboard the
ill-fated passenger plane to survive five days after the crash,
the worst ever in the Philippine history.
</P>
<P>
Jesus Dureza, a rescue operation leader, told reporters that
rescuers had retrieved six bags of scattered body parts and 11
bodies in the surrounding vicinity of Mt. Sumagaya in Claveria
Town, Misamis Oriental Province as of 6 p.m. local time Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The plane's 99 passengers included one Japanese, an Austrian, a
Swiss, at least two Americans, an Australian and at least one
Canadian.
</P>
<P>
The twin-engine aircraft, owned by Cebu Pacific Airways,
slammed into Mt. Sumagaya Monday morning while trying to land at
the nearby airport of Cagayan de Oro City, some 800 km south of
its departure place Manila.
</P>
<P>
Bitterly cold rain and low visibility grounded helicopters for
much of the day and slowed rescue operations as rescuers crawled
along the steep slopes to recover the bodies and the wreckage of
the plane.
</P>
<P>
Dureza said rescuers had tried to move the bodies by air from
the crash site to Manibay, a military base in Claveria town on the
foot of Mt. Sumagaya, but failed due to bad weather in the area.
</P>
<P>
Dureza said the bodies could be transported by foot Friday
morning to Manibay where a group of forensic experts headed by the
National Bureau of Investigation (NBI) will conduct examination to
identify the bodies.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Health is sending more mental health experts
to Calveria and Cagayan de Oro to provide disaster debriefing to
the hundreds of anguished relatives of the victims.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
