<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Sets Up Social Security System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 6 (Xinhua) -- A comprehensive social
security system is taking shape in China's largest city of
Shanghai to provide relief for all the needy.
</P>
<P>
The system, named "Warmth Project", has in the last two years
issued more than 300 million yuan in relief to 500,000 needy
residents in the city to ensure minimum living standards.
</P>
<P>
In 1993 the municipality took the country's lead in
setting a bottom line to ensure minimum living standards for its
urban people. Following that, the bottom income line for laid-off
workers was also set to help financially-troubled state-owned
firms.
</P>
<P>
A computerized network has linked the needy together.
</P>
<P>
The Trade Union of Shanghai, which focuses its efforts on
helping the needy workers, has established files for 100,000 poor
workers and issues 40 million yuan in relief for them every year.
</P>
<P>
The project also takes measures to help those residents who are
financially stranded and seriously ill. Governments, communities,
hospitals and individuals are asked to join hands to shoulder the
burden. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
