<HEADLINE> U.S. to Provide More Food Aid to DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 5 (Xinhua) -- The United States will
provide 200,000 tons of food for the Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK) in response to a United Nations appeal for
humanitarian aid, the State Department said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin said at a briefing that
a U.S. team visited the DPRK last year and confirmed outside
assessments that the 1997 harvest "fell well short" of meeting the
nation's food needs and substantial food aid would be needed to
avert serious food shortages this year.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. assistance will be targeted at children in
nurseries; schools and orphanages; pregnant and nursing women;
handicapped people and hospital patients.
</P>
<P>
To ensure that the donated food is used as intended, the World
Food Program will nearly double its international staff there to
46, including 26 food monitors, and will create two regional
offices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
