<HEADLINE> European Shares End Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 5 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
all ended higher Thursday, with Paris hitting a new record high,
supported by steady interest rates, further merger hopes and Asian
markets' strong overnight performance.
</P>
<P>
Britain's FTSE 100 index of leading shares had surged 79 points
to its intraday all-time peak of 5,675.1 earlier during the
session before ending 10.6 points up at 5,606.4 as late
profit-taking took the market off the fresh record high.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that unchanged UK, US and German interest rates,
hopes of further big mergers and solid overnight performances in
Asian markets had propelled the London market to a new high.
</P>
<P>
But Wall Street's inability to hold early opening gains
contributed to London's late retreat.
</P>
<P>
German shares in Frankfurt closed a quiet floor trade session
61.51 points higher at 4,548.46, with sentiment buoyed by gains on
Asian markets and positive technical factors.
</P>
<P>
The CAC-40 index ended 23.34 points up at 3,189.60, a fresh
record close although well down from a historic intra-day high as
profit-taking wiped some of its earlier gains.
</P>
<P>
The softer dollar and weaker Wall Street also curbed the
market's advance.  
</P>
</TEXT>
