<HEADLINE> Ambassador Qin on the Question of the Central </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 5 (Xinhua) -- China will give a
positive consideration to UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan's
recommendation of establishing a UN peace keeping operation in the
Central African Republic, Chinese Ambassador to the United Nations
Qin Huasun said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Qin made the remarks before the Security Council of the United
Nations adopted a resolution on the Central African Republic. In
the resolution, the Council authorized to extend the mandate of
the Inter-African Mission to Monitor the Implementation of the
Bangui Agreements (MISAB). The Council also decided to make a
decision by March 16, 1998, on the establishment of a UN
peacekeeping force in the country.
</P>
<P>
Qin said China has been following closely the development of
the situation in the Central African Republic, and China
sincerely hopes that this country can walk out of the crisis at
an earliest possible time so that its people can lead a happy
and stable life.
</P>
<P>
Qin said China is in favor of a further extension of the
mandate of MISAB so as to support efforts in helping the
Government of the Central African Republic and parties concerned
to resolve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Ambassador said China will also give a positive
consideration to the UN chief's recommendations of setting up a UN
peacekeeping Operation in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
