<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More U.S. Troops Sent to Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 5 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton has
decided to send about 2,200 U.S. Marines on board warship from the
Mediterranean to the Gulf to join the already might military force
in the region as time ticks close to a possible military showdown
with Iraq over its refusal to allow weapons inspectors's access to
presidential areas, defense officials said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 24th marine Expeditionary Unit aboard the helicopter
carrier Guam and three support ships would move through the Suez
Canal into the Red Sea and then to the Gulf in about 10 days.
</P>
<P>
They would join a force of some 20 other U.S. warships,
including the aircraft carriers Nimitz, George Washington. And the
third aircraft carrier Independent also entered the Gulf region on
Thursday with 75 aircraft aboard and a battle group that includes
a cruiser, a destroyer and a submarine.
</P>
<P>
The United States now has more than 150 strike warplanes and
dozens of support aircraft aboard a trio of carriers, as well as
about 175 other tactical planes at bases in Saudi Arabia, Kuwait
and Bahrain. And there are about 20 U.S. combat ships in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
the additional 2,200 marines were requested by Marine Corps
General Anthony Zinni, chief of the U.S. Central Command and the
commander of all American forces in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Zinni has also asked for an additional six radar-avoiding
F-117A stealth fighters to join six of the planes already
stationed in Kuwait and another six B-52 bombers to join eight
stationed on the Indian Ocean island of Diego Garcia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
